"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828244","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-16","<p><strong>As a routine, departments publish quarterly details of Ministers’ meetings with external organisations on GOV.UK, including those with representatives from companies such as Carillion. Cabinet Office returns can be viewed using the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</strong></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-16T14:27:43.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828244/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828244/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828244/answer/previousversion/37130","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-22","Cabinet Office: Keith Cochrane","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings with Ministers Keith Cochrane attended in his role on the Government Network of non-Executive directors.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","124204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828245","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>Children’s centre inspections are suspended. There was widespread agreement at the time that they were not fit for purpose. As indicated in the letter of 25 September 2015 to HM Chief Inspector of Education, the Secretary of State for Education retains the ability to require Ofsted to undertake inspections and Ofsted itself retains the ability to inspect children’s centres if concerns are raised. The letter can also be viewed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centre-inspections-sam-gyimah-letter" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centre-inspections-sam-gyimah-letter</a>.</p><p> </p><p>This suspension should not affect the normal activity of children’s centres and we expect them to continue their work to improve the outcomes for children and families in local areas. Registered early years provision within children’s centres will continue to be inspected by Ofsted as part of the Common Inspection Framework.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold a list of children’s centres that have not received five-year inspections as a result of the suspension. However, this information can be derived from publicly available data. Records of Ofsted inspections of children’s centres and children’s centre groups carried out between 2010 and 2015, including a list of names and addresses and the date of the last inspection are at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-centres-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-centres-statistics</a>. Real-time data on the current list of children’s centres and children’s centre groups including names and address is supplied by local authorities via the Get Information about Schools (GIAS) database portal at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","124199 ; 124206","2018-01-25T17:24:31.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828245/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828245/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Children's Centres: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the number of children's centres which would have received a five year inspection before 31 December 2017 but did not as a result of his Department suspending such inspections in September 2015.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","124205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828246","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>Children’s centre inspections are suspended. There was widespread agreement at the time that they were not fit for purpose. As indicated in the letter of 25 September 2015 to HM Chief Inspector of Education, the Secretary of State for Education retains the ability to require Ofsted to undertake inspections and Ofsted itself retains the ability to inspect children’s centres if concerns are raised. The letter can also be viewed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centre-inspections-sam-gyimah-letter" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sure-start-childrens-centre-inspections-sam-gyimah-letter</a>.</p><p> </p><p>This suspension should not affect the normal activity of children’s centres and we expect them to continue their work to improve the outcomes for children and families in local areas. Registered early years provision within children’s centres will continue to be inspected by Ofsted as part of the Common Inspection Framework.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold a list of children’s centres that have not received five-year inspections as a result of the suspension. However, this information can be derived from publicly available data. Records of Ofsted inspections of children’s centres and children’s centre groups carried out between 2010 and 2015, including a list of names and addresses and the date of the last inspection are at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-centres-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/childrens-centres-statistics</a>. Real-time data on the current list of children’s centres and children’s centre groups including names and address is supplied by local authorities via the Get Information about Schools (GIAS) database portal at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","124199 ; 124205","2018-01-25T17:24:31.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828246/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828246/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Children's Centres: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, where the children's centres are which have not received a five-year inspection as a result of the suspension of inspections imposed in September 2015.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","124206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828247","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>In England, 20% of pupils were in outstanding and 70% were in good primary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p>Ofsted inspection data shows that in Cornwall, 20% of pupils were in outstanding and 69% were in good primary schools as at August 31, 2017. In North Cornwall, 9% of pupils were in outstanding, and 77% were in good primary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p>In England, 28% of pupils were in outstanding and 55% were in good secondary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p>Ofsted inspection data also shows that in Cornwall 10% of pupils were in outstanding and 78% were in good secondary schools as at August 31, 2017. In North Cornwall, 10% of pupils in outstanding and 78% were in good secondary schools as at August 31, 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted’s latest statistics are available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-30T16:36:42.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828247/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828247/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Schools: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the proportion of (a) primary and (b) secondary age children in (i) Cornwall and (ii) North Cornwall who attend a school rated (A) outstanding and (B) good by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","124207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828248","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-30","<p>Data on the reuse or recycling of such items is not held centrally. Recycling practices are decided locally between the relevant providers and commissioners, though there is a responsibility on National Health Service trusts to make the best use of all resources and items including recycling and reuse of aids where it is safe and cost effective to do so.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-30T12:13:33.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828248/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828248/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-22","Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) crutches, (b) walking frames, (c) wheelchairs and (d) similar items are recycled for use by more than one patient.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","124208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828249","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-26","<p>The latest available estimates from the Waste and Resources Action Programme are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Estimates_%20in_the_UK_Jan17.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Estimates_%20in_the_UK_Jan17.pdf</a></p><p>These estimates are not broken down further by region.</p><p> </p><p>Other information through permit data for waste sent to landfill would not provide a robust estimate since much of the food waste would be recorded as part of mixed municipal waste rather than just for food waste.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-26T15:45:03.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828249/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828249/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-22","Food: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of food waste which went into landfill (a) nationally and (b) in Cornwall in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","124209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828250","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>We have noted the publication of findings from the survey regarding early years teachers, conducted by Save the Children in collaboration with Nursery World, published on 22 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to fund the 'Early Years Initial Teacher Training' programme, including bursaries and employer incentives.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-25T15:23:33.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828250/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828250/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Pre-school Education: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the implications are for his Department's policies on the early years workforce of findings from the Nursery World and Save the Children survey on training and employing early years teachers, published on 22 January 2018.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","124210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828251","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>As confirmed in our response to parliamentary question 123170, there are no targets for recruiting early years teachers in the workforce. This has always been a demand-led programme and we continue to make early years initial teacher training places available based on this basis.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-25T17:39:28.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828251/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828251/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Teachers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2018 to Question 123170, on what date the recruitment target for such teachers was dropped.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","124211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828252","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Department does not ordinarily collect information about procurement activity since local authorities and academy trusts are responsible for their own contracts. Information available to the department indicates that the number of local authority and academy trust schools covered by services contracts with Carillion is relatively low, and significantly lower than figures initially published on Carillion’s website. Schools affected already have robust contingency plans in operation and, for many, this may include transferring services in house, or re-procuring with alternative providers. We are working closely with the Official Receiver, Special Manager and local authorities to confirm the position.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-25T17:35:33.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828252/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828252/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2018 to Question 123193, which (a) local authorities and (b) academy trusts have contracts with Carillion for school support services; and for each such school what the type of service provided is.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","124212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828253","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Prime Minister wrote to President Weah to congratulate him on his election victory, and I share those sentiments. Our Ambassador in Monrovia and a senior official from London attended President Weah's inauguration on 23<sup>rd</sup> January, and discussed early priorities with him.</p><p>The UK's relationship with Liberia is an historic one. Britain was the first country to recognise Liberia's independence in 1848. The Foreign Secretary made the first ever visit to Liberia by a serving UK Foreign Minister in February 2017. My predecessor as Minister for Africa, Rory Stewart, met with a delegation of Liberian Ministers in September. The UK financial commitment to Liberia is approximately £70m annually and our Embassy in Monrovia will work closely with the new administration to help deliver our shared priorities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-29T16:53:39.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828253/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828253/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-22","Liberia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to meet President Weah of Liberia; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","124213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828254","Department for Education","false","2018-01-31","<p>Local authorities and academy trusts are responsible for their own contracts. Information available to the Department indicates that the number of schools covered by services contracts with Carillion across England is relatively low, including a small number of schools in the Barnsley local authority area. The Department is working closely with both with the Official Receiver and the local authority to confirm the position.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has worked with local authorities and academy trusts to make sure they have robust contingency plans in place and that these have been actioned, where required. The Department is continuing to monitor developments and provide support where it is needed to help minimise any disruption.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-31T13:42:51.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828254/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828254/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on schools in the Barnsley local authority area which hold contracts with Carillion.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","124214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828255","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-25","<p>The information requested is not held at Jobcentre level and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>As outlined in the response to PQ 121780, each Work Coach receives comprehensive and tailored training based on their individual knowledge and requirements. The mental health route way forms part of the UC Full Service Work Coach training, and all work coaches working on Full Service will have undertaken this.</p><p>In addition to Work Coach support, the Department has also recruited local Community Partners to provide extra expertise on disability and health conditions. Furthermore, our Disability Employment Advisors actively provide advice and guidance to support claimants with disabilities, including those with mental health issues.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-25T16:34:05.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828255/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828255/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-22","Jobcentre Plus: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many work coaches in each job centre have received mental health training.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","124215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828256","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-30","<p>The introduction of compulsory microchipping of all dogs in 2016 has greatly reduced the number of stray dogs needing rehoming, because the stray dog and their owner can now be quickly reunited. According to the Dogs Trust’s annual Stray Dogs Survey Report, the number of stray dogs has dropped from 126,000 in 2011 to just over 66,000 in 2017. In addition my Department has been working with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group (a group of animal welfare, pet industry and veterinary organisations) to promote more responsible advertising of pet animals, and to reduce impulse buying that so often leads to dogs being abandoned or handed in to re-homing charities. We are also updating the laws on the breeding and selling of dogs which will require all licensees to provide relevant information about pet ownership for prospective buyers, so that informed choices can be made before a purchase is made.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-30T16:26:41.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828256/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828256/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-22","Stray Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to support work to re-home stray and abandoned dogs.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","124216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828257","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has ministerial responsibility for the Social Mobility Commission.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-25T16:53:08.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828257/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828257/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-22","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he has ministerial responsibility for the Social Mobility Commission.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","124217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828258","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Department did not award a High Speed Two contract to Carillion in July 2017. A joint venture called CEK JV (comprising Carillion, Eiffage and Kier) was awarded the contract in July 2017. HS2 Ltd undertook due diligence on the CEK Joint Venture prior to the MWCC Award in July. The CEK Joint Venture met the required financial standing criteria. HS2 has carried out additional due diligence and sought re-assurance of both Joint Venture partners, Kier and Eiffage, that they remain committed and capable to deliver the contract. Each company's Boards have both given that assurance and confirmed that they underwrite the performance of each other and have the capacity to deliver the HS2 contract.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-25T15:11:23.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828258/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828258/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-22","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department made an assessment of the viability of Carillion to deliver on its contractual responsibilities and remain solvent prior to awarding the company a High Speed Two contract in July 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","124218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828259","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-29","<p>A breach of the statutory Code of Practice for the Welfare of Horses, Ponies, Donkeys and their Hybrids is not an offence itself but if proceedings are brought against a person for an offence under the Animal Welfare Act 2006, the Court will look at whether or not the person complied with the code in deciding whether they have committed an offence.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-29T18:13:10.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828259/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828259/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-22","Horses: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make it his policy to make failure to abide by the Code of Practice for the Welfare of Horses, Ponies, Donkeys and their hybrids a criminal offence.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","124219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828260","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The bus market in England (outside London) is deregulated and operated by private sector bus operators. The deregulated bus market works well across much of the country and any operational decisions are a matter for individual operators, as is the ownership model they wish to consider.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Bus Services Act 2017 presents local authorities with new powers to bring about change, and unlock the potential for the bus industry to achieve more for passengers. In particular, new enhanced partnership and advanced quality partnership powers provide the framework for authorities to work side by side with operators to set a shared vision for bus services in their area.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-29T11:17:10.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828260/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828260/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-22","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of the use of a cooperative model of ownership for bus services.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","124220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828261","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Government has not assessed the use of a cooperative model of ownership for gas or water.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-25T10:30:29.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828261/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828261/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-22","Utilities: Cooperatives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of the use of a cooperative model of ownership for gas and water providers.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","124221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828262","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-30","<p>As the Chancellor set out in his 2017 Mansion House speech, the EIB has been an important source of finance for infrastructure investment in the UK. The EIB invests across a range of sectors including energy, transport, housing, education, water and sewerage.</p><p> </p><p>For the green industry, the EIBs largest and most frequent loans over the last decade have been in the field of renewable energy generation, more specifically; offshore wind farms and offshore transmission networks <em>(through OFGEMs offshore transmission network tendering process).</em></p><p> </p><p>From 2006-2016 the EIB lent €15.69bn to the UK energy sector. Of this, roughly a quarter was to projects related to offshore wind generation.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB has also lent to other types of environmentally focussed projects such as the rollout of Smart Meters and the Thames Tideway Tunnel.</p><p> </p><p>A complete database of all EIB projects and loan amounts can be found at the link below;</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB" target="_blank">http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-30T12:55:18.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828262/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828262/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-22","Industry: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2018 to Question 122491, what assessment his Department has made of the contribution of European Investment Bank funding to the UK's green industry.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","124222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828263","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-29","<p>The EU guidelines (December 2017) acknowledge the proposal put forward by the UK for a time-limited implementation period, based on the existing structure of EU rules and regulations. Both parties have recognised the importance of such a period in the interests of providing certainty and continuity to businesses and individuals. The UK wants to agree the detail early in 2018 to provide certainty as quickly as possible. In the meantime, the Government will continue to work closely with the EU to ensure the UK’s rights as an EU Member State are respected.</p><p>Leaving the EU also offers opportunities for DFID and UK NGOs, and we will support our NGOs to make the most of these opportunities in future.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-29T17:27:13.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828263/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828263/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-22","Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that the work of UK-based humanitarian NGOs is not adversely affected by the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","124223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828264","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-30","<p>Britain is a development superpower. We have world class development organisations delivering aid to those who need it most. In 2016, UK NGOs received around €200 million in new ECHO funding commitments. NGOs are making their own assessments of the effect of losing access to ECHO funding, which they have been discussing with me periodically as we prepare to leave the EU.</p><p>We are working as part of the negotiations on the future EU funding instruments to ensure that third country organisations have access to these instruments in the next few months.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-30T16:39:43.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828264/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828264/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-22","Non-governmental Organisations: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect on the work and effectiveness of UK-based humanitarian NGOs of those organisations losing access to ECHO funding as a result of the UK leaving the EU .","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","124224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828265","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-19","<p>UK NGOs are important partners for ECHO. In 2016, 24 out of 136 partners who received funding from ECHO were UK-based (or 17.6%). UK-based partners received more funding than those from any other countries.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-02-19T15:10:29.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828265/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/828265/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-22","Non-governmental Organisations: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of ECHO funding has gone to UK-based humanitarian NGOs in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","124225"
