"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825695","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-25","<p>According to the latest Conversion Factors for Company Reporting, published in August 2017, the conversion factor of incineration of any waste material is 21.8 kg CO2e per tonne. Therefore each tonne of waste that is incinerated will release 21.8 kg CO2e of emissions.</p><p> </p><p>Source: Conversion Factors 2017, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635632/Conversion_factors_2017_-_Condensed_set__for_most_users__v02-00.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635632/Conversion_factors_2017_-_Condensed_set__for_most_users__v02-00.xls</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-25T12:04:14.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825695/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825695/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-19","Incinerators: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on the amount of  CO2e that is emitted for every tonne of waste that is incinerated.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825696","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-26","<p>An estimate of recycling rejects for all local authority collected waste is reported as part of the annual England local authority waste statistics which are published within the datasets (Table 3b for All Local Authority Waste) at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env18-local-authority-collected-waste-annual-results-tables" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env18-local-authority-collected-waste-annual-results-tables</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the rejection of waste at materials recycling facilities (MRF) is not specifically collated and published, so is not readily available. The estimate of all recycling rejections for the last three years is summarised in the table below and will include any rejections recorded at the point of collection, at the MRF or at the gate of the reprocessor.</p><p> </p><p>The reasons for the rejection of waste are not recorded by the local authorities.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-26T14:51:49.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825696/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825696/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-19","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much and what proportion of waste was rejected by materials recycling facilities in each of the last three years; and for what reasons that waste was so rejected.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825697","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>HS2 Ltd undertook due diligence on all bids prior to the Main Works Civils Contract Award in July. Each of the joint venture parties individually and collectively were covered. The CEK joint venture has provided HS2 Ltd with assurances that in the event of any member of the group being unable to deliver on its responsibilities, the remaining members, now Eiffage and Kier, would fill the gap.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-29T11:06:58.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825697/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825697/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what financial assessment he made of Carillion before agreeing a contract for HS2 development with an SPV of which Carillion was a composite part.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","123765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825698","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Secretary of State did not award the contract himself, he delegated authority to do so to HS2 Ltd. The Secretary of State did not receive reports on the shorting of Carillion shares prior to the award, by HS2 Ltd, of the two Main Works Civils Contracts to the unincorporated Joint Venture.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-29T10:38:10.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825698/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825698/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he received reports of market short-selling in relation to Carillion when he offered a contract for HS2 development to an SPV of which Carillion was a composite part.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","123766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825699","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Task and Finish group on Taxi and Private Hire Vehicles was established by the then Minister of State for Transport, John Hayes, and has received submissions from a number of disability representation organisations. I look forward to receiving the group’s findings soon.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","123769","2018-01-29T09:30:02.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825699/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825699/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to secure participation by disabled people on the taxi and private hire vehicle working group.","false","Biography information for Sandy Martin","Ipswich","Sandy Martin","123767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825700","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-26","<p>All waste operators, including local authorities, are required under the Waste Framework Directive to take account of the waste hierarchy when considering the provision of services around their waste management. The waste hierarchy places prevention at the top as it offers the best outcome for the environment, followed by preparing for reuse, recycling, other recovery (which includes energy from waste) and then disposal. Landfill should only be considered as a last resort.</p><p> </p><p>The incineration of waste with energy recovery (also known as energy from waste) plays an important role in diverting waste from landfill but it must not compete with greater prevention, reuse and recycling of waste.</p><p> </p><p>England’s recycling rate has increased to 44.9% and the Government has signalled clear ambitions for resource efficiency in the Clean Growth Strategy, Industrial Strategy and 25 Year Environment Plan, which set out an ambition for zero avoidable waste by 2050. We are committed to supporting comprehensive and frequent waste and recycling collections which protect local amenity and ensure that products are recycled as much as possible. The Government is developing a new strategy on resources and waste to be published later this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-26T14:56:17.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825700/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825700/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-19","Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2017 to Question 115115, what steps he (a) is taking and (b) proposes to take to ensure that in future such waste is used higher up the waste hierarchy.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825701","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Task and Finish group on Taxi and Private Hire Vehicles was established by the then Minister of State for Transport, John Hayes, and has received submissions from a number of disability representation organisations. I look forward to receiving the group’s findings soon.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","123767","2018-01-29T09:30:02.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825701/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825701/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to ensure that the needs of people with various disabilities are represented on the taxi and private hire vehicle working group.","false","Biography information for Sandy Martin","Ipswich","Sandy Martin","123769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825702","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-05","<p>These roles were advertised on the website of the Centre for Public Appointments, and the Cabinet Office received 32 applications. Selection was made on the following advertised criteria:</p><p>Essential:</p><ul><li>Ability to work at a senior level and command the confidence and trust of key stakeholders, including those subject to the Rules.</li><li>Ability to analyse complex information from a range of sources, identify key issues and make objective and balanced decisions on complex issues.</li><li>An understanding of the issues around the perception of outside appointments for former crown servants</li><li>Evidence of effective working as part of a team.</li><li>Excellent communication skills both written and oral.</li></ul><p>Desirable:</p><ul><li>Experience of dealing with conflicts of interest.</li></ul><p> </p><p>​These appointments were made on merit following fair and open competition, in line with the requirements of the Governance Code for Public Appointments.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","123771","2018-02-05T14:45:17.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825702/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825702/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Business Appointments Advisory Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the three appointments to the Advisory Committee on Business Appointments announced on 18 January 2018, how those positions were advertised and how many applications were received.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825703","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-05","<p>These roles were advertised on the website of the Centre for Public Appointments, and the Cabinet Office received 32 applications. Selection was made on the following advertised criteria:</p><p>Essential:</p><ul><li>Ability to work at a senior level and command the confidence and trust of key stakeholders, including those subject to the Rules.</li><li>Ability to analyse complex information from a range of sources, identify key issues and make objective and balanced decisions on complex issues.</li><li>An understanding of the issues around the perception of outside appointments for former crown servants</li><li>Evidence of effective working as part of a team.</li><li>Excellent communication skills both written and oral.</li></ul><p>Desirable:</p><ul><li>Experience of dealing with conflicts of interest.</li></ul><p> </p><p>​These appointments were made on merit following fair and open competition, in line with the requirements of the Governance Code for Public Appointments.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","123770","2018-02-05T14:45:17.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825703/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825703/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Business Appointments Advisory Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the three appointments to the Advisory Committee on Business Appointments announced on 18 January 2018, what the selection criteria for those appointments were.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825704","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-30","<p>The latest available estimates from the Waste and Resources Action Programme are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Estimates_%20in_the_UK_Jan17.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Estimates_%20in_the_UK_Jan17.pdf</a>.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-30T16:21:46.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825704/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825704/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-19","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question 117523, if he will make an estimate of the amount of food waste that goes to (a) landfill and (b) incineration.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825705","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-26","<p>Details of DFID funding to 31 December 2017, under the Ross Fund portfolio, to tackle tuberculosis, malaria, and HIV/AIDS, are outlined below:</p><p> </p><p>Tuberculosis: £16.25 million</p><p>Malaria: £32.13 million</p><p>HIV/AIDS: £10.2 million</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-26T14:55:10.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825705/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825705/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-19","Ross Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much of the Ross Fund her Department has spent on tackling  (a) tuberculosis, (b) malaria and (c) HIV/AIDS since that fund was established.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","123773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825706","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department has no projects funded through the Ross Fund Portfolio which exclusively address tuberculosis, malaria or HIV/AIDS. The Ross Fund Portfolio is spent cross-government and research programmes that address these diseases are currently managed by the Department for International Development.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-29T16:50:20.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825706/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825706/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Ross Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much of the Ross Fund his Department has spent on tackling (a) tuberculosis, (b) malaria and (c) HIV/AIDS since that fund was established.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","123774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825708","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-26","<p>Our humanitarian aid operates under International Humanitarian Law and is provided based on need. As such it is available to people of all faiths and of none. All our partners carry out comprehensive vulnerability assessments to ensure aid is reaching those most in need, including those from religious minorities as it is already recognised that religion may be a factor in causing vulnerability.</p><p>We keep this under close review. For example, we will take on board the outcomes of a roundtable between UNHCR, local faith leaders and faith-based NGOs which was convened in Amman, Jordan by our Embassy officials on 23 January. This forum discussed UNHCR’s systems for ensuring impartiality and assessing vulnerability and protection needs (including resettlement opportunities) for refugee groups of all faiths.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-26T12:46:29.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825708/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825708/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-19","Developing Countries: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if her Department will make an assessment of whether its aid delivered through UN agencies is reaching religious minorities.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","123775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825709","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The UK is a world leader in the fight to stamp out the brutal practice of forced marriage, with our dedicated Forced Marriage Unit (FMU) leading efforts to combat it both at home and abroad. The FMU gives advice or support through its public helpline or by email. In 2012, this amounted to 1,485 cases related to a possible forced marriage; 1,302 cases in 2013; 1,267 cases in 2014; 1,220 cases in 2015; and 1,428 cases in 2016. The FMU public statistics are published annually here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu</a>. The FMU works closely with UK statutory agencies such as the police and social services, but does not refer cases directly to the Crown Prosecution Service.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-24T14:22:44.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825709/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825709/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-19","Forced Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many cases were referred to the Forced Marriage Unit in (a) 2012, (b) 2013, (c) 2014, (d) 2015 and (e) 2016; how many of those cases were referred to the Crown Prosecution Service in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825710","Department for Education","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Government wants to ensure all pupils can benefit from a high quality education. The Department is committed to supporting all good and outstanding schools, including selective schools that wish to expand, particularly where there is demand for more good school places and it can be demonstrated that the change represents the best local solution and value for money. However, the legislative ban on opening new grammar schools remains in place.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is continuing to work with the grammar schools sector to ensure that more academically able children from low-income backgrounds can secure a place at selective schools, and to encourage selective schools to work with other local schools to help improve standards locally.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-24T17:00:51.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825710/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825710/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-19","Grammar Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what his policy is on grammar schools; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","123777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825711","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department welcomes the Civil Aviation Authority’s (CAA) call for a change in the current regulations and their decision to issue initial Class 1 Medical certificates with a restriction to multi-pilot operations to applicants wishing to become commercial pilots, subject to the applicants passing their Class 1 Medical assessment. The CAA has often led aviation regulatory changes that have enabled pilots with medical conditions to keep flying, and I welcome their continued efforts to see a permanent change to the current regulations at the European level.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-29T16:57:35.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825711/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825711/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Aviation: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will respond to Early Day Motion 827 on HIV and UK aviation.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","123778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825712","Department for Education","false","2018-01-30","<p>In November 2015, there were 19.3 full-time equivalent teachers (FTE) without Qualified Teacher Status employed by all academies in the Cambridge constituency. This represents 7.5% of all full time equivalent teachers in academies in the Cambridge constituency.</p><p>In November 2016, this rose to 22.4 FTE teachers and represents 8.2% of all FTE teachers in academies in the Cambridge constituency. This is the latest year for which information is available.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-30T17:15:54.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825712/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825712/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825712/answer/previousversion/37868","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-01-19","Academies: Cambridge","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many unqualified teachers worked in academies in Cambridge constituency in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17; and how many unqualified teachers are working in academies in that constituency.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","123779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825713","Department for Education","false","2018-01-29","<p>The department has not received any formal complaints on a change of curriculum at academies that used to be maintained schools in the Cambridge constituency.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-29T17:20:17.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825713/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825713/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-19","Academies: Cambridge","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many complaints have been received on a change of curriculum at academies that used to be maintained schools in Cambridge constituency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","123780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825714","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-26","<p>The UN estimates there is a major financing gap of around $2.5 trillion p.a. for developing countries in delivering the Sustainable Development Goals which will need to be met by the public and private sector. The Private Finance Initiative (PFI) is specific to the UK context, and used as the primary model of Public Private Partnerships in the UK. There is no internationally agreed definition of either a PFI or a PPP. However, DFID supports developing countries in many ways to mobilise private finance, including through forms of Public-Private Partnerships. This is unlikely to include UK style PFI projects. DFID’s approach mobilises much needed private investment in infrastructure and other sectors where private sector activity is limited. This includes projects financed through CDC, the World Bank Group, the regional development banks and the Private Infrastructure Development Group. In some of these investments the government of the developing country will be the end purchaser of the services. In all our work DFID has a strong emphasis on value for money.</p><p>The Public-Private Partnerships that DFID supports play an important role in providing access to services that might otherwise not exist in those countries. In the absence of this type of support, developing country governments would need to raise capital in debt markets to meet the costs of these essential investments.</p><p>[Details on the range of Public-Private Partnership projects that DFID supports can be found on the following websites: <a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</a>; <a href="http://www.cdcgroup.com/" target="_blank">http://www.cdcgroup.com/</a>; <a href="http://www.worldbank.org/" target="_blank">http://www.worldbank.org/</a>; <a href="https://www.afdb.org/en/" target="_blank">https://www.afdb.org/en/</a>; <a href="https://www.adb.org/" target="_blank">https://www.adb.org/</a>; <a href="https://www.aiib.org/en/index.html" target="_blank">https://www.aiib.org/en/index.html</a>; <a href="https://www.iadb.org/en" target="_blank">https://www.iadb.org/en</a>; <a href="http://www.caribank.org/" target="_blank">http://www.caribank.org/</a>; <a href="http://www.ebrd.com/" target="_blank">http://www.ebrd.com/</a>; <a href="http://www.eib.org/" target="_blank">http://www.eib.org/</a>; <a href="http://www.pidg.org/" target="_blank">http://www.pidg.org/</a> and <a href="http://data.pidg.org/" target="_blank">http://data.pidg.org/</a>]</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-26T14:55:22.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825714/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825714/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-19","Developing Countries: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many PFI projects her Department is funding through its international development aid budget; and what those projects are.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825715","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-30","<p>The UN estimates there is a major financing gap of around $2.5 trillion p.a. for developing countries in delivering the Sustainable Development Goals which will need to be met by the public and private sector. There is no internationally agreed definition of a Public Private Partnership (PPP). However, DFID supports developing countries in many ways to mobilise private finance, including through forms of Public-Private Partnerships. DFID’s approach mobilises much needed private investment in infrastructure and other sectors where private sector activity is limited. This includes projects financed through CDC, the World Bank Group, the regional development banks, and the Private Infrastructure Development Group. In some of these investments the government of the developing country will be the end purchaser of the services. In all our work DFID has a strong emphasis on value for money.</p><p> </p><p>The Public-Private Partnerships that DFID supports play an important role in providing access to services that might otherwise not exist in those countries. In the absence of this type of support, developing country governments would need to raise capital in debt markets to meet the costs of these essential investments.</p><p> </p><p>Details on the range of Public-Private Partnership projects that DFID supports can be found on the following websites: <a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</a>; <a href="http://www.cdcgroup.com/" target="_blank">http://www.cdcgroup.com/</a>; <a href="http://www.worldbank.org/" target="_blank">http://www.worldbank.org/</a>; <a href="https://www.afdb.org/en/" target="_blank">https://www.afdb.org/en/</a>; <a href="https://www.adb.org/" target="_blank">https://www.adb.org/</a>; <a href="https://www.iadb.org/en" target="_blank">https://www.iadb.org/en</a>; <a href="http://www.caribank.