"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825763","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>NHS England will be launching a consultation on the contracting arrangements for Accountable Care Organisations (ACOs) in March. No ACO contract will be awarded in the meantime.</p><p> </p><p>There is widespread support for ending the fragmented way that care has been provided to improve services for patients and the National Health Service has been working towards this in a number of ways. ACOs are just one of these ways and are intended to allow health and care organisations to formally contract to provide services for a local population in a coordinated way.</p><p> </p><p>An ACO is not a new type of legal entity and so would not affect the commissioning structure of the NHS. An ACO would simply be the provider organisation which is awarded a single contract by commissioners for all the services which are within scope for the local accountable care model. Therefore any proposal to award an ACO contract would engage local commissioners’ own duties under the NHS Act 2006. Any area seeking to use an ACO contract would need to comply with longstanding public procurement law.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will set out how the contract fits within the NHS as a whole, address how the existing statutory duties of NHS commissioners and providers would be performed under it (including how this will work with existing governance arrangements), and will set out how public accountability and patient choice would be preserved.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to the outcome of the consultation, the two areas at the forefront of using a contract of this sort are Dudley, and Manchester’s proposed local care organisation. These are the only two areas that NHS England currently understands may be in a position to award an ACO contract during 2018. Emerging bidders for both proposals are NHS bodies, have the support of local general practitioners and are not private sector organisations. In two further areas, clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have launched procurement exercises for integrated service providers. Scarborough CCG has confirmed that it does not intend to use a contract based on the draft ACO contract. The last is Northumberland CCG.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold a copy of any agreement or memorandum of understanding.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-29T12:27:26.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825763/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825763/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Accountable Care Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the four local areas are where a procurement process to establish an accountable care organisation is underway according to the NHS Providers document entitled STPs and accountable care - background briefing, of 15 January 2018;  what stage each of those processes has reached; and if he will place a copy of any agreement or memorandum of understanding between those areas and NHS England and NHS Improvement in the Library.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825764","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>Prior to approval, all Private Finance 2 proposals should be assessed in line with The HM Treasury’s Green Book, including a comparison against an appropriate publicly funded option.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-29T11:25:19.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825764/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825764/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the National Audit Office report on PFI and PF2 published on 18 January 2018, what assessment he has made of the benefits of using publicly financed procurement with fixed-price contracts instead of private finance initiatives.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825765","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) is currently scoping the programme of urgent works at HMP Liverpool. There are no plans to publish any of these investment proposals.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-29T17:37:45.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825765/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825765/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to publish his investment proposal for a medium-term refurbishment programme for HMP Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825766","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>No cups were purchased directly by the Cabinet Office.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-12T14:04:26.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825766/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825766/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Cabinet Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825767","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>We have no plans currently to conduct such a review. Prior to approval, all privately financed contracts should be assessed in line with HM Treasury’s Green Book.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-29T11:23:20.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825767/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825767/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Public Private Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the National Audit Office report on PFI and PF2 published on 18 January 2018, whether his Department plans to conduct a review of the use of PFI and PF2 contracts and their long-term value for money.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825768","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>HM Treasury does not have information about the use and recycling of disposable coffee cups within the department. Facilities management services in 1 Horse Guards Road are provided to HM Treasury under a 35 year PFI agreement with Exchequer Partnerships Plc. Cups are provided by Exchequer Partnership’s subcontractor.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-29T11:31:55.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825768/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825768/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Treasury: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825769","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>HMP Liverpool have commissioned a training needs analysis to look at the training needs of our staff for 2018-19. The local branch of the Prison Officers Association (POA) at HMP Liverpool will be invited to take part in these discussions by the Governor.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-29T17:43:18.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825769/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825769/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans there are for the involvement of the Prison Officers Association and other staff representatives in developing HMP Liverpool’s annual training plan for 2018.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825770","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>Since 29 September 2017, when considering the review period for an Employment and Support Allowance or Universal Credit claimant as part of the Work Capability Assessment, a healthcare professional has been required to consider whether the condition or its functional affects meet the new severe conditions criteria. Where the criteria are all met, the healthcare professional will advise that no further assessments are needed.</p><p>Rather than being defined through a list of specific medical conditions, the criteria are based on identifying claimants with severe, lifelong, often progressive and incurable illnesses and disabilities, whose level of function would always mean that they would have Limited Capability for Work and Work-Related Activity, and who are unlikely ever to be able to move into work.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-29T16:39:10.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825770/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825770/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-19","Employment and Support Allowance: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department is taking steps to ensure that those diagnosed with Parkinson's disease are not declared as having a condition which is likely to improve by employment support allowance physical assessors; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825771","Home Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The coffee cups provided in 2 Marsham Street are biodegradable, and staff and visitors are encouraged to compost these in the facilities provided.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-01-29T17:59:01.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825771/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825771/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-19","Home Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased bought by her Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825772","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-26","<p>The POA have been engaged locally by the new Governor of HMP Liverpool, on the issues raised by the inspectorate. The Governor is committed to ongoing engagement as improvement plans are implemented.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-26T12:23:41.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825772/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825772/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions his Department has had with the Prison Officers Association and other staff representatives on the future of HMP Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825773","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>The below table highlights the available information held on the number of disposable cups purchased in the UK by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in each of the last five years. The figures are based on cups purchased centrally by our catering supplier. They do not include individual ad hoc purchases of cups by teams within the office or purchases by our overseas missions.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Hot beverage cups</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>Data not available</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>Data not available</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>Data not available</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p>654,156</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p>655,718</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Since May 2017, the FCO have provided disposable cup recycling bins and offered discounts on hot drinks purchased in reusable cups in its food and drink outlets to minimise disposable cup waste and support the recycling of disposable cups.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-01-29T17:55:43.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825773/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825773/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-19","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825774","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-30","<p>The information on how many disposable cups were purchased by the Ministry of Defence is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-30T15:10:23.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825774/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825774/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-19","Ministry of Defence: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825775","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>Prison Service Instruction 17 of 2012 sets out that it is the responsibility of the Prison Group Director to ensure that all cells are correctly certified, and recorded on a cell certificate schedule which is signed by the PGD.</p><p> </p><p>Published information on the levels of crowding at HMP Liverpool can be found in the National Offender Management Service Annual digest 2016/17:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","123849","2018-01-29T17:38:56.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825775/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825775/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether HMP Liverpool is operating with an operational capacity that involves a level of crowding above its Certified Normal Accommodation.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825776","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>I can confirm that the MoJ holds a partial amount of the information that you have requested and I have provided it below.</p><p> </p><p>My response is primarily restricted to purchases made via a Catering Disposable contract which commenced in June 2017 and has since supplied Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service. Comparative data for periods prior to June 2017 is not held.</p><p> </p><p>I can provide the data for 2017/18 to date as per below;</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number of disposable hot beverage cups</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18 (Part year Apr 17 to date)</p></td><td><p>929,960</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-01-29T17:23:42.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825776/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825776/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Ministry of Justice: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825777","Home Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>There is no policy to pay a penalty for the late reimbursement of Immigration Visa fees or charges similar to the Immigration Health Surcharge.</p><p>The published Immigration Health Surcharge refund SLA is;<br>“You usually get your refund within 6 weeks of getting a decision on your visa application. It can take longer if you appeal or ask for an administrative review after your visa application is refused.”<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/healthcare-immigration-application/refunds" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/healthcare-immigration-application/refunds</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-24T16:20:40.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825777/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825777/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-19","Immigrants: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department is liable to a penalty in respect of late payment of Immigration Health Surcharge reimbursements; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825778","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>The action plan for HMP Liverpool refers to 172 places [for prisoners] taken out of use at the prison. As these places were taken offline over a period of time and in consultation with the Governor at HMP Liverpool the capacity of the prison has been reduced since the Inspection.</p><p> </p><p>These changes were managed as part of business as usual activity in the prison over a short period of time, this was possible due to the nature of HMP Liverpool’s role as a local prison with their high level of turnover of prisoners. There has been no increase in two or more prisoners sharing cells at the prison since the inspection, either in terms of number of individuals or in terms of percentage of the prison’s total population.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","123819 ; 123828","2018-01-29T17:37:14.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825778/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825778/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions his Department has had with the Governor of HMP Liverpool on (a) the operational capacity of the prison and (b) cell occupancy at the prison since the closure of the 172 cells referred to in Action Plan: HMP Liverpool, published on 19 January 2018.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825779","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-22","<p>The number of offenders sentenced to indeterminate sentences and released by the Parole Board, once they had completed their tariff, and who have gone on to re-offend, can be found in the Quarterly Proven Re-Offending Statistics published by the MoJ .</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Table: Adult proven reoffending data, by custodial sentence length</strong><sup>1</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016 Q1 </strong><sup>3</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Indeterminate sentence for public protection</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of reoffenders</p></td><td><p>53</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of offenders in cohort</p></td><td><p>389</p></td><td><p>376</p></td><td><p>453</p></td><td><p>137</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mandatory life prisoner</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of reoffenders</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of offenders in cohort</p></td><td><p>172</p></td><td><p>113</p></td><td><p>185</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Other life</strong><sup> 2</sup></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of reoffenders</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of offenders in cohort</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>90</p></td><td><p>102</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of reoffenders</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>87</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of offenders in cohort</p></td><td><p>654</p></td><td><p>579</p></td><td><p>740</p></td><td><p>214</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes</strong>:</p><p>1. Data regarding offenders released from indeterminate sentences up to September 2015 are extracted from the Public Protection Unit Database (PPUD). As data were not of sufficient quality for these offenders prior to 2009, they have not been included in the figures. Data regarding offenders released from indeterminate sentences from October 2015 onwards are extracted from nDelius.</p><p>2. 'Other life' category includes discretionary and automatic life sentences.</p><p>3. Data from April 2016 are not yet published.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Parole Board will release prisoners serving an indeterminate sentence after they have completed the tariff set by the Court, where it is satisfied that it is no longer necessary for public protection for them to remain in prison. Offenders released by the Parole Board are supervised on licence by the National Probation Service</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-22T17:28:17.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825779/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825779/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders who were granted early release from prison by the Parole Board have re-offended in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","123846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825780","Department for Education","false","2018-01-29","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. Disposable coffee cups are purchased by an external catering supplier, which was unable to provide this information.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-29T17:34:46.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825780/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825780/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-19","Department for Education: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825781","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) is accommodated in buildings owned by other government departments. The provision of disposable cups and the management of their disposal is overseen by the landlords for each building.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","123149","2018-01-23T17:21:54.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825781/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825781/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many disposable coffee cups have been purchased by his Department since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825782","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-29","<p>Prison Service Instruction 17 of 2012 sets out that it is the responsibility of the Prison Group Director to ensure that all cells are correctly certified, and recorded on a cell certificate schedule which is signed by the PGD.</p><p> </p><p>Published information on the levels of crowding at HMP Liverpool can be found in the National Offender Management Service Annual digest 2016/17:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","123842","2018-01-29T17:38:56.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825782/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825782/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-19","Liverpool Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cells at HMP Liverpool that were designed for single occupancy have been certified by the relevant Prison Group Director in accordance with PSI 17/2012 to accommodate two prisoners or more.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825783","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>Special advisers are appointed in accordance with the rules on the appointment of Special Advisers set out in the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010, and in line with the Ministerial Code and the Special Adviser Code of Conduct.</p><p>A named list of all special advisers was published in December, as per the Written Ministerial Statement of 14 December 2017, Official Report, HCWS352. https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2017</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-21T14:41:30.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825783/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825783/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Cabinet Office: Former Members","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many former Conservative Members of Parliament who were defeated at the 2017 general election and who now work in his Department were appointed after a publicly advertised and open recruitment process.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","123850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825784","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-29","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Disposable coffee cups used within the department are purchased by an external catering supplier, who is unable to provide this information.</p><p> </p><p>Staff and visitors are encouraged to dispose of waste appropriately and use recycling facilities where it is appropriate to do so.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-01-29T14:15:02.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825784/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825784/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-19","Department for International Trade: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many disposable coffee cups have been purchased by his Department since it's establishment.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825785","Home Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>Should a customer wish to seek reimbursement for the costs of replacing a lost document, they are advised to contact UKVI and they will be dealt with on a case by case basis in accordance with the complaints procedure:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about/complaints-procedure</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-24T16:21:34.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825785/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825785/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-19","Visas: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what penalties her Department is liable for in respect of the loss of people's identification documents relating to visa applications.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825786","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Department was created in July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s catering supplier, Baxter Storey, purchased the following disposable cups for use in the staff restaurants and coffee shops:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>No. of cups</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>60,832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>48,912</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department makes provision for recycling and has specially marked recycling bins throughout the Department.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-25T12:05:08.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825786/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825786/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-19","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825787","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department does not purchase disposable coffee cups directly. The Department used single use disposable cups on its estate in the numbers in the table and cannot specify how many were specifically for hot drinks. The cups were served from the cafes and restaurants on its estate and purchased by its catering supplier. Information is not held prior to October 2014.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>October 2014 to September 2015</p></td><td><p>332,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2015 to September 2016</p></td><td><p>340,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016 to September 2017</p></td><td><p>325,220</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-29T12:30:57.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825787/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825787/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Department of Health and Social Care: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825788","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The department (including Executive Agencies) has not purchased any disposable coffee cups in the last five years, except the DVSA made one purchase of 3,000 cups in 2016 for conferences. None have been purchased since. In the central Department staff bring their own cups in for any teas or coffees they wish to make for themselves.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-29T17:05:53.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825788/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825788/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Department for Transport: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825789","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-25","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. Disposable coffee cups are purchased by an external catering supplier, which was unable to provide this information.</p><p><br>The catering facilities in the Department’s headquarters office in 2 Marsham Street are provided through the Home Office. The coffee cups used in the Department’s headquarters office in 2 Marsham Street are biodegradable.</p><p><br>Staff and visitors are encouraged to dispose of waste appropriately and userecycling bins where it is appropriate to do so.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-25T16:53:05.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825789/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825789/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-19","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825790","Scotland Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Scotland Office does not have any in-house canteen or coffee shop facilities, and as such, no disposable coffee cups were purchased in each of the last five years.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-01-25T13:13:39.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825790/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825790/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-01-19","Scotland Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825791","Wales Office","false","2018-01-26","<p>None.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-01-26T10:54:13.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825791/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825791/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-01-19","Wales Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825792","Home Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>Hizballah's External Security Organisation was proscribed in March 2001 and in 2008 the proscription was extended to Hizballah's military apparatus including the Jihad Council.</p><p>Proscription means that an organisation is outlawed and is unable to operate in the UK. It is a criminal offence for a person to: <br>• belong to or invite support for a proscribed organisation; <br>• arrange a meeting in support of a proscribed organisation;<br>• wear clothing or carry articles in public which arouse reasonable suspicion that an individual is a member or supporter of the proscribed organisation. <br> <br>The penalties for proscription offences can be a maximum of 10 years in prison and/or an unlimited fine.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2018-01-25T12:43:16.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825792/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825792/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-19","Hezbollah","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to prevent the promotion of the military wing of Hezbollah in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825793","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Northern Ireland Office has, in 2015 purchased 1,500 disposable cups, in 2016 purchased 1,000 and in 2017 purchased 5,000. Records relating to purchases of cups in the previous two years are not held.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-01-25T11:11:58.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825793/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825793/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-19","Northern Ireland Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by her Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825794","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-31","<p>Since October 2014, the number of disposable coffee cups purchased by Defra’s catering provider has fallen by a third:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Disposable coffee cups </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2014- September 2015</p></td><td><p>440,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2015- September 2016</p></td><td><p>323,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016–September 2017</p></td><td><p>297,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The contractor does not hold this level of data for more than 3 years. These figures do not account for plastic and other disposable cups. Defra has not purchased any disposable coffee cups.</p><p> </p><p>The current catering contract expires this summer. The tender for the new contract stipulates that the supplier must not use single use plastics and must provide alternatives to single use coffee cups or implement a recycling scheme.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-31T19:13:32.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825794/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825794/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-19","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825795","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department for International Development has a zero tolerance approach to UK aid funds being diverted to fund terrorist activities and the UK Government publishes a list of prescribed extremist groups or organisations banned under UK law. Where there are allegations of misuse of aid funds, these are investigated fully by the Department’s specialist Counter Fraud Unit, and funds are always recovered to the fullest extent possible.</p><p>The Department has robust measures in place to protect, prevent, and detect the diversion of aid. Controls are embedded through-out the programme cycle and are continually revised and adapted to meet evolving threats and changes in operational circumstances. The Department has recently strengthened its already rigorous due diligence process and comprehensive risk management framework which requires risks to be identified prior to the disbursement of UK aid.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T17:23:19.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825795/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825795/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-19","Overseas Aid: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent steps she has taken to prevent UK development aid funding being used to support international terrorism.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825796","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-26","<p>We are unable to provide purchasing data prior to 2017. In 2017 DFID London purchased approximately 4,300 ‘Vegware’ cups every month. Made from plant material – not plastic – these cups are organic, compostable and can be recycled with the food waste. In 2017 DFID Scotland took delivery of approximately 3,000 card and plastic cups. There are schemes in both DFID offices to encourage use of reusable coffee cups, with 10% off the price of a coffee when staff use their own cup. In DFID Scotland reusable cups are available for purchase, with the aim of bringing down the number of disposable coffee cups used.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-26T12:44:09.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825796/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825796/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-19","Department for International Development: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by her Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825797","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The information requested is not held centrally, and to obtain it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-29T14:15:00.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825797/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825797/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-19","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many disposable coffee cups were purchased by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","123864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825798","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>I sympathise with those who have been adversely affected by severe weather conditions recently.</p><p> </p><p>The establishment of financial support schemes for damage caused by severe weather conditions is a devolved matter. As such, it would be a matter for Northern Ireland departments to consider and I have made no assessment as to the powers available to them in this regard.</p><p> </p><p>More broadly, the fundamental issue is and remains the absence of Northern Ireland Ministers to take political decisions. The broader strategic decisions needed to tackle some of the key challenges facing Northern Ireland requires political direction to progress. That should be provided by local politicians through a power-sharing Executive, and that is why it is essential that we see devolution restored.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-01-24T17:35:55.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825798/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825798/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-19","Weather: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the Permanent Secretaries of devolved Departments in Northern Ireland have the authority to set up financial support schemes to address damage caused by severe weather conditions.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825799","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-29","<p>We are concerned about terrorist attacks in Egypt that have targeted the Coptic community and at reports of sectarian violence. Combating sectarian violence is a shared strategic objective for the Egyptian and British Governments and we welcome President Sisi's calls for peaceful coexistence between communities. The Government of Egypt has stated its commitment to protecting the rights of minorities and of the need for religious tolerance, and the Egyptian constitution contains protection for Freedom of Religious Belief. It is important that these rights are respected.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-29T16:46:39.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825799/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825799/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-19","Egypt: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the treatment of Christians in Egypt.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825800","Home Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>Discussions with the US Administration on their proposals for the pre-clearance in the UK of passengers travelling to the US are ongoing, and no decision has yet been made.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-25T12:44:09.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825800/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825800/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-19","Aviation: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the US State Department on introducing US pre-clearance to airports in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825801","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>Project Bank Accounts (PBAs) are the preferred option by government when it is considered best value for money for taxpayers, and we have made a commitment in the Government Construction Strategy to use PBAs unless there are compelling reasons not to. Over £10bn has been spent in this way on a wide range of projects between 2011 and 2015.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-24T17:29:34.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825801/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825801/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of the Government setting up project bank accounts for each public sector project to protect suppliers in the light of the liquidation of Carillion.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","123868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825802","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-23","<p>The government has committed to extending a zero rate of VAT to women’s sanitary products as soon as we are legally able to.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-01-23T15:28:47.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825802/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825802/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Sanitary Protection: VAT Zero Rating","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will introduce a VAT zero rate on women's sanitary products immediately after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825803","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>Under devolution arrangements, policy relating to ports and harbours in Northern Ireland is a matter for the Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p> </p><p>Officials at the Department for Transport have, however, been in contact with ports in Northern Ireland as well as ports elsewhere in the UK to discuss issues relating to EU exit.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","123872","2018-01-29T10:58:47.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825803/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825803/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Belfast Harbour","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has conducted a recent review of the capacity of Belfast Port.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825804","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Government is aware that the largest UK SME lending banks have set out their plans to help SMEs exposed to the liquidation of Carillion. While the support offered is a commercial decision for each bank to take, the Government will continue to engage with the banking industry on how best to support these small businesses.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-01-24T17:35:10.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825804/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825804/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Economic Secretary to the Treasury of 18 January 2018, Official Report, column 1128, what the timetable is for Lloyds Bank to maintain its support for SMEs affected by the liquidation of Carillion.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","123871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825805","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>Under devolution arrangements, policy relating to ports and harbours in Northern Ireland is a matter for the Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p> </p><p>Officials at the Department for Transport have, however, been in contact with ports in Northern Ireland as well as ports elsewhere in the UK to discuss issues relating to EU exit.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","123870","2018-01-29T10:58:47.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825805/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825805/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Port of Larne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the capacity of Larne Port.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825806","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-24","<p>The nature of Carillion business means that it sub-contracts significant proportions of its work, with the potential for those sub-contractors to sub-contract out further elements. The complexity of the contracting structure is such that it is not possible for Government at this stage in the liquidation process to have a complete picture of the number of SMEs affected.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-24T16:39:35.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825806/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825806/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-19","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the number of SMEs affected by the liquidation of Carillion.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","123873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825807","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-24","<p>My rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, and I are working to ensure information is provided to SMEs in the Carillion supply chain in a timely manner.</p><p>The Secretary of State has chaired two meetings of a taskforce to advise on the impact on small businesses affected by the Carillion insolvency on 18 and 22 January. The taskforce’s attendees included representatives from leading business bodies, the construction trade sector, unions, banks and government.</p><p>In addition I have met leading business and construction trade bodies, representing Carillion’s sub-contractors, on 3 occasions in the last 10 days to understand the impact of Carillion’s insolvency on the supply chain, and agree actions that could be taken to mitigate this. It is our intention to continue to meet regularly with this group on an ongoing basis.</p><p>The Secretary of State and I met major high street lenders on 17 January 2018 to seek assurances that they will not penalise small businesses affected by Carillion’s liquidation. Lenders are contacting customers and, where appropriate, are putting in place emergency measures, including overdraft extensions, payment holidays and fee waivers to ensure those facing short term issues can be helped to stay on track. Details of these can be found at</p><p><a href="https://www.ukfinance.org.uk/banks-offer-support-to-business-customers-impacted-by-carillion/" target="_blank">https://www.ukfinance.org.uk/banks-offer-support-to-business-customers-impacted-by-carillion/</a>.</p><p>The Department is providing a range of advice and support services for firms, delivered both nationally and locally available to SMEs affected by the insolvency of Carillion. These include a network of 38 Local Growth Hubs, run in conjunction with the Local Enterprise Partnership, to help businesses of all sizes and in all sectors to access support.</p><p>Information is published online by the Insolvency Service for employees, creditors and suppliers affected and seeking advice. In addition to providing current information, they provide a dedicated hotline for enquiries and contact numbers to other relevant organisations such as the Pensions Advisory Service, and the website PwC have been established to provide information.</p><p>These can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/carillion-declares-insolvency-information-for-employees-creditors-and-suppliers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/carillion-declares-insolvency-information-for-employees-creditors-and-suppliers</a>.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-24T16:40:03.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825807/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825807/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-19","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support he plans to give to SMEs affected by the liquidation of Carillion.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","123874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825808","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-24","<p>It is important that small businesses have access to the appropriate forum to address their concerns with the financial services that they have received, including where they believe wrongdoing has occurred. The Government welcomes the publication of the Financial Conduct Authority’s paper on small businesses as customers of financial services firms, and is carefully considering its findings.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-01-24T12:51:41.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825808/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825808/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Financial Services: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Economic Secretary to the Treasury of 19 January 2018, Official Report, column 1126, what steps he plans to take to change the culture to enable wrongdoing to be exposed and dealt with.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","123875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825809","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>The information requested for numbers of requested Universal Credit advances is not available. However, data on advances paid in the Universal Credit Full Service is included below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>New Claim advances</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Benefit Transfer advances</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Change of Circumstance advances</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Claims paid an advance</p></td><td><p>As a proportion of <strong>new</strong> claims</p></td><td><p>Claims paid an advance</p></td><td><p>As a proportion of <strong>all</strong> claims</p></td><td><p>Claims paid an advance</p></td><td><p>As a proportion of <strong>all</strong> claims</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Jun</p></td><td><p>6,800</p></td><td><p>43%</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Jul</p></td><td><p>7,600</p></td><td><p>43%</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Aug</p></td><td><p>9,100</p></td><td><p>42%</p></td><td><p>1,100</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>900</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Sep</p></td><td><p>8,400</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td><td><p>2,000</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Oct</p></td><td><p>12,400</p></td><td><p>47%</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17-Nov</p></td><td><p>19,600</p></td><td><p>58%</p></td><td><p>3,400</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>1,600</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","123903 ; 123904","2018-01-24T17:17:21.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825809/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825809/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of new claimants of universal credit (a) requested a new claim advance and (b) received a new claim advance in each month from 5 June 2017 up to and including 31 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","123876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825810","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government has been engaging and will continue to engage with industry, including LINK, to ensure that this access is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any formal assessment of the potential effect of LINK’s proposals to change the interchange fee rate on consumers, small businesses, the North Dorset constituency or other rural communities. However, the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p> </p><p>LINK has assured us and the PSR that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK intends to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in areas of deprivation, where demand would not otherwise make one viable, and has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","123789 ; 123790 ; 123793 ; 123878 ; 123880 ; 123881","2018-01-29T11:37:37.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825810/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825810/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Cash Dispensing: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of LINK’s proposed reduction of the interchange fee on (a) consumers and (b) small businesses.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","123877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825811","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government has been engaging and will continue to engage with industry, including LINK, to ensure that this access is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any formal assessment of the potential effect of LINK’s proposals to change the interchange fee rate on consumers, small businesses, the North Dorset constituency or other rural communities. However, the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p> </p><p>LINK has assured us and the PSR that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK intends to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in areas of deprivation, where demand would not otherwise make one viable, and has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","123789 ; 123790 ; 123793 ; 123877 ; 123880 ; 123881","2018-01-29T11:37:37.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825811/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825811/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Cash Dispensing: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the number of ATMs that will be withdrawn as a result of a 20 per cent reduction in the LINK interchange fee.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","123878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825812","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>We have provided no such guidance.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has issued general guidance to National Health Service organisations on the sale of advertising space to generate additional income. The guidance is clear that third party advertisements should not suggest that the NHS endorses or recommends the advertiser’s goods or services. It can be found at the following web address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/nhsidentity/faq/can-an-nhs-organisation-sell-advertising-space-to-generate-income/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/nhsidentity/faq/can-an-nhs-organisation-sell-advertising-space-to-generate-income/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-29T14:31:21.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825812/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825812/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what guidance his Department provides to NHS Trusts on the provision of private healthcare leaflets in NHS hospitals advertising medical services.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","123879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825813","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government has been engaging and will continue to engage with industry, including LINK, to ensure that this access is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any formal assessment of the potential effect of LINK’s proposals to change the interchange fee rate on consumers, small businesses, the North Dorset constituency or other rural communities. However, the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p> </p><p>LINK has assured us and the PSR that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK intends to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in areas of deprivation, where demand would not otherwise make one viable, and has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","123789 ; 123790 ; 123793 ; 123877 ; 123878 ; 123881","2018-01-29T11:37:37.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825813/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825813/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Cash Dispensing: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of ATM closures resulting from LINK’s proposed reduction in the interchange fee on (a) North Dorset constituency and (b) other rural communities.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","123880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825814","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government has been engaging and will continue to engage with industry, including LINK, to ensure that this access is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any formal assessment of the potential effect of LINK’s proposals to change the interchange fee rate on consumers, small businesses, the North Dorset constituency or other rural communities. However, the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p> </p><p>LINK has assured us and the PSR that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK intends to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in areas of deprivation, where demand would not otherwise make one viable, and has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","123789 ; 123790 ; 123793 ; 123877 ; 123878 ; 123880","2018-01-29T11:37:37.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825814/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825814/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-19","Cash Dispensing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department has had with LINK on (a) the proposed reduction in the interchange fee and (b) the Financial Inclusion Programme.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","123881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825815","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-25","<p>We are committed to assessing people with health conditions and disabilities fairly and accurately, helping people to access the right support. We recognise the importance of getting reform in this area right. We therefore intend to focus on testing new approaches to build our evidence base for future reform. In the Improving Lives: The Future of health, Work and Disability command paper we committed to work with external stakeholders to inform future changes to the Work Capability Assessment.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-25T10:22:59.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825815/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825815/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-19","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will undertake an end-to-end review of her Department's approach to the work capability assessment process.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825816","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-29","<p>We have provided no such guidance.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has issued general guidance to National Health Service organisations on the sale of advertising space to generate additional income. The guidance is clear that third party advertisements should not suggest that the NHS endorses or recommends the advertiser’s goods or services. This guidance is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/nhsidentity/faq/can-an-nhs-organisation-sell-advertising-space-to-generate-income/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/nhsidentity/faq/can-an-nhs-organisation-sell-advertising-space-to-generate-income/</a></p><p> </p><p>Patients who choose to pay for additional private care or services, such as private hearing aid services, will not lose their entitlement to NHS services, which remain free at the point of delivery.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-29T12:18:13.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825816/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825816/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Hearing Aids: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what guidance his Department provides to NHS trusts on the advertisement of private hearing aid services in NHS hospitals.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","123883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825817","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-26","<p>Sanctions are only ever used as a last resort. When considering whether a sanction is appropriate, a Decision Maker will take all the claimant’s individual circumstances, including any health conditions or disabilities and any evidence of good cause, into account before deciding whether a sanction is warranted.</p><p> </p><p>We engage at a personal and individual level with all of our claimants and are committed to tailoring the support that we give and any conditionality requirements to the specific circumstances of the individuals.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","123803","2018-01-26T14:01:48.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825817/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825817/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-19","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to mitigate any potential effects of welfare sanctions on claimants' mental health and wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825818","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-26","<p>The Department has not made such an assessment, as meaningful activities are different for each individual. We work in partnership with our claimants to ensure that their programme of work-related activity is tailored to, and agreed with, the claimant to provide the best possible outcome in each case.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-26T14:01:42.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825818/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825818/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of using meaningful activity instead of work as an outcome measure for people receiving welfare payments.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825819","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Government already has in place a range of grant funding schemes to assist with the cost of installing dedicated domestic chargepoints in the homes of electric vehicle drivers as well as in workplaces, for the use of employees and fleets. Grant support also exists for Local Authorities to support the installation of chargepoints in residential areas without access to off-street parking. These grants are available to support chargepoints for all types of battery electric vehicles.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-29T09:10:33.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825819/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825819/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-19","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has plans to subsidise domestic and business-based charging points for high capacity battery electric cars; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","123886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825820","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>In October 2017 the Care Quality Commission reported 80% of adult social care providers had been rated as good or outstanding. However, when standards fall below those rightly expected by care home residents and their families, it is right that information is shared across the system. The Department is working with the adult social care sector to implement Quality Matters – a shared commitment to take action to achieve high quality, person-centred adult social care. This includes actions to improve information collection and sharing and to support organisations to improve care services.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission has provided the following response:</p><p> </p><p>There are a range of meetings by which the Care Quality Commission and local authorities share information. There are also protocols, and requirements that exist to coordinate between the Care Quality Commission and local authorities. For Inadequate or Requires Improvement services, if the Care Quality Commission take certain enforcement action, such as issuing a notice of proposal or a notice of decision, there is a requirement to share notices with the Association of Directors of Social Care Service and other relevant partners such as clinical commissioning groups.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission inspectors regularly communicate with staff in local authorities as part of their everyday routine engagement, which informs inspection planning and whether risk needs to be escalated, or if joint visits are required.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-24T12:17:52.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825820/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825820/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Care Homes: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government is taking to improve the way local authorities and the Care Quality Commission (a) coordinate inspections of and (b) share information on care homes classed as (i) requiring improvement and (ii) inadequate.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","123887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825821","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Care Act 2014 placed duties on local authorities to shape their local markets to ensure all adult social care service users have a choice of high quality services. The Department is working with the Care Quality Commission and partners across the adult social care sector to implement Quality Matters – a shared commitment to take action to achieve high quality, person-centred adult social care.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission has provided the following response:</p><p> </p><p>The Care Quality Commission introduced an updated inspection methodology from 1 November for adult social care services, including care homes. The new methodology took into account learning from the inspection and rating of these services from October 2014 onwards as well as undertaking a public consultation in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Changes introduced include more proportionate and targeted inspections; a stronger regulatory focus on services rated as requires improvement, using enforcement powers to require providers to take action when they need to improve; improvements in identifying, monitoring and responding to risks; developing and sharing information from providers, collected online, as a single shared view of quality; and on reporting, making reports clearer and more informative, including reference to serious incidents.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-24T12:23:08.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825821/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825821/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Care Homes: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government is taking to improve the regulation and oversight of the performance of care homes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","123888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825822","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>There are no existing bodies or processes which review the joint performance of the Care Quality Commission and clinical commissioning groups on care home inspections. The Department is working with the Care Quality Commission, NHS England and partners across the adult social care sector to implement Quality Matters – a shared commitment to take action to achieve high quality, person-centred adult social care.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-01-24T12:24:03.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825822/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825822/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-19","Care Homes: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what (a) bodies and (b) processes there are to review the joint performance of the Care Quality Commission and Clinical Commissioning Groups on care home inspections.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","123889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825823","Department for Education","false","2018-01-24","<p>The government will conduct a major review of funding across tertiary education. In the Industrial Strategy, it was stated that the review will consider a range of specific issues within post-18 education.</p><p> </p><p>The government will set out further details on the review shortly.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-01-24T16:49:33.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825823/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825823/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-19","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to Industrial Strategy: building a Britain fit for the future, published on 27 November 2017, if he will make it his policy to extend the Government's major review of funding across tertiary education to include the education system for people aged 16 years and over.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825824","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-24","<p>Nothing is more important than keeping people safe. That is why we established the Building Safety Programme, which has been working with local authorities and building owners to identify properties that might be at risk. A variety of interim safety measures have also been put in place so that everyone is kept safe. A list of these measures can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/648775/Update_on_Interim_Mitigation_Measures_290917.pdf." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/648775/Update_on_Interim_Mitigation_Measures_290917.pdf.</a></p><p><br>The programme is working with local authorities across England to make sure that all building owners take necessary remedial action to improve the fire safety of tower blocks as swiftly as possible.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-24T15:06:54.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825824/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825824/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-19","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that combustable material including cladding and insulation is removed from tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","123891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825825","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>BEIS have recently introduced a payment reporting system, which requires large businesses to report on their UK payment practices and performance. Businesses must report 6 monthly on their payment performance starting with their first full financial year that starts on or after 6 April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Government departments publish their own payment performance data on GOV.UK. We encourage suppliers that have not been paid promptly to report the case to our Mystery Shopper Service, who will investigate on their behalf.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-24T17:29:24.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825825/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825825/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-19","Business: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department has taken (a) generally and (b) in respect of Carillion to monitor and enforce the requirement that prime contractors pay undisputed, valid invoices within 30 days and ensure that such terms are implemented throughout the supply chain since 26 February 2015; and if he will publish performance data for each prime contractor for his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","123892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825826","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-24","<p>The department does not foresee the liquidation of Carillion impacting our ability to deliver on the government's broadband roll out programme.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-24T16:33:33.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825826/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825826/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-19","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the liquidation of Carillion on the roll-out of broadband across the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","123893"
