"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823443","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Advisory Council publishes its own annual report which is laid before Parliament. Since the transition from the 30 year rule to 20 year rule began in 2013, the Advisory Council has collated and published annual figures on closures and retention, and the outcomes of these applications. The Council also reports on the work of its Freedom of Information Panels. The information can be found in its annual reports, available at <a href="http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/about/our-role/plans-policies-performance-and-projects/our-performance/" target="_blank">http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/about/our-role/plans-policies-performance-and-projects/our-performance/</a></p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","122922","2018-01-24T16:30:38.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823443/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823443/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-18","Advisory Council on National Records and Archives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many documents the Advisory Council on National Records and Archives has withheld in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","122921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825376","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-18","<p>Road users will have noticed no difference following the switch of operation from Severn River Crossings PLC to public ownership and Highways England management on 8 January 2018, except for the reduction in cost. VAT has already been scrapped and there will be no charges at all by the end of the year.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-18T13:27:46.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825376/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825376/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-18","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","What assessment he has made of the effect on road users of the Severn Bridges being taken into public ownership.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","903380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825377","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-18","<p>I would be delighted to meet representatives from the Kettering rail users group, and my hon. Friend.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-18T13:07:13.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825377/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825377/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-18","Railways: Kettering","1","House of Commons","If the Rail Minister will meet the Kettering Rail Users Group.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","903384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825378","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-18","<p>HS2 will help transform the UK economy, directly creating 25,000 new jobs - 70 percent of which will be outside of London. It will directly link 8 of the UK’s 10 largest cities and provide a step change in the country’s railway capacity. The Government regularly assesses the benefits of HS2 through the economic and strategic business cases.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-18T13:32:44.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825378/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825378/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","What assessment he has made of the potential benefits of High Speed Two for the Midlands and the north.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","903387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825410","Department for Education","false","2018-01-26","<p>The government recognises the importance of supporting pupils at school with medical conditions. Section 100 of the Children and Families Act 2014 introduced a duty that requires governing boards to make arrangements to support pupils with medical conditions. Most schools manage these issues well and take their responsibilities towards pupils with such conditions seriously, making sure that the medical needs of their pupils are being met.</p><p>The department works with organisations such as the Health Conditions in Schools Alliance to raise awareness of the duty, and recently promoted it through the department’s social media channels.</p><p>Governing boards should ensure that schools develop a policy for supporting pupils with medical conditions that is reviewed regularly and is readily accessible to parents and school staff. We keep the guidance under review, including in the context of school awareness, and the role it plays in securing accessibility of school policies.</p><p>This guidance is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supporting-pupils-at-school-with-medical-conditions--3" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supporting-pupils-at-school-with-medical-conditions--3</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","123554","2018-01-26T11:57:10.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825410/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825410/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Pupils: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department has taken to raise awareness of schools of their duty to protect and enable pupils with medical conditions.","false","Biography information for Sandy Martin","Ipswich","Sandy Martin","123553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825411","Department for Education","false","2018-01-26","<p>The government recognises the importance of supporting pupils at school with medical conditions. Section 100 of the Children and Families Act 2014 introduced a duty that requires governing boards to make arrangements to support pupils with medical conditions. Most schools manage these issues well and take their responsibilities towards pupils with such conditions seriously, making sure that the medical needs of their pupils are being met.</p><p>The department works with organisations such as the Health Conditions in Schools Alliance to raise awareness of the duty, and recently promoted it through the department’s social media channels.</p><p>Governing boards should ensure that schools develop a policy for supporting pupils with medical conditions that is reviewed regularly and is readily accessible to parents and school staff. We keep the guidance under review, including in the context of school awareness, and the role it plays in securing accessibility of school policies.</p><p>This guidance is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supporting-pupils-at-school-with-medical-conditions--3" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supporting-pupils-at-school-with-medical-conditions--3</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","123553","2018-01-26T11:57:11.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825411/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825411/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Pupils: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans his Department has to require all maintained schools to have a medical conditions policy and to display such a policy publicly on their school website; and if he will make statement.","false","Biography information for Sandy Martin","Ipswich","Sandy Martin","123554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825412","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-29","<p>The Department for Communities in Northern Ireland has responsibility for the delivery of Universal Credit in Northern Ireland, which it does with the support of DWP and the Universal Credit Programme.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit has been introduced in Northern Ireland for new claims on a phased geographical basis by post code groups aligned to front office locations. This process started from September 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-29T15:42:02.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825412/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825412/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Universal Credit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the implementation in parts of Northern Ireland of universal credit; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","123555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825413","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Foreign Secretary has made clear that the Iranian people should be able to freely express themselves and to demonstrate peacefully within the law. We look to the Iranian authorities to permit this. We are concerned by reports of mass arrests and deaths in custody, and by restrictions on freedom of expression, in particular the suspension of popular messaging application, Telegram.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T10:06:20.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825413/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825413/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-18","Iran: Protest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect on human rights of the actions of the Iranian government during the protests that took place in that country from 28 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","123556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825414","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>On 11 January, the Foreign Secretary discussed Iran's response to the protests with Foreign Minister Zarif. In addition, on 5 January, we supported the proposal to discuss the protests at the UN Security Council where we set out our human rights concerns strongly.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T14:20:57.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825414/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825414/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-18","Iran: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department took in response to the restrictions placed by the Iranian Government on the instant messaging service Telegram; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","123557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825415","Department for Education","false","2018-01-23","<p>I refer the hon. Member for St Helens and Whiston, to the answer I gave on 19 January 2018 to Question 122942: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-01-16/122942/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-01-16/122942/</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-23T17:13:07.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825415/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825415/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to section 1(1) of the Childcare Act 2016, what steps he is taking to ensure that childcare is available free of charge for disabled three and four-year-old children for a period equivalent to 30 hours in each of 38 weeks in any year.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","123739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825416","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-25","<p>Where a Work Capability Assessment and Personal Independence Payment health professional’s report is examined by a Decision Maker that person will look to see if there are obvious flaws. For Example, if there are any contradictions or inconsistencies or omissions within that report. If that report is considered unacceptable or requires clarification the Decision Maker or Quality Assurance Manager will contact the assessment provider for clarification, advice or to return the report for re-work as unacceptable.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-25T10:22:29.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825416/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825416/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department provides on allowing disability benefit assessors to provide feedback on mistakes or errors that occur during health assessments to improve the assessment process.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","123740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825417","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>Although this Department has overall responsibility for the Housing Benefit scheme and its funding, local authorities have the statutory responsibility for its day-to-day administration. This incorporates the assessment of individual claims for benefit and devising their own arrangements to assist claimants (including those with chronic and enduring mental illnesses) with claims for Housing Benefit.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-23T11:30:35.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825417/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825417/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Housing Benefit: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to help people with chronic and enduring mental illnesses make an application for housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","123558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825418","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>DWP work coaches support people with disabilities and health conditions every working day and the Department has delivered additional training to 1,800 work coaches to support claimants with mental health conditions.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has also recruited local Community Partners to provide extra expertise on disability and health conditions. Furthermore, our Disability Employment Advisors actively provide advice and guidance to support claimants with disabilities, including those with mental health issues.</p><p> </p><p>If someone cannot access the online Universal Credit service on their own, DWP staff will help them make a claim and can also refer them to DWP funded local services which offer assisted digital and personal budgeting support. Universal Support provides extra help for claimants to make and maintain their claim and to manage their money.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants can also claim over the phone, which is free to use, and where necessary, appointees can also make a claim on a claimant’s behalf and help maintain their online account. In circumstances where a claimant is unable to visit their local Jobcentre or conduct their business with DWP using other channels, home visits are also available.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-23T11:30:48.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825418/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825418/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Universal Credit: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to help people with chronic and enduring mental illnesses make an application for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","123559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825419","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-13","<p>Foxes can carry a range of parasites and diseases relevant to the health of people and domestic pets. There is, however, no evidence that foxes are a major risk to public health, or to pet dogs in England. Britain is currently rabies-free and measures are in place to keep it that way.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-13T11:32:22.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825419/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825419/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","Foxes: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential health risks caused by the urban fox population; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","123560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825420","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-26","<p>We are making good progress towards our efficiency targets, and are confident of meeting our objectives. This work will help provide assurance that our current plans are robust.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-26T13:44:53.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825420/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825420/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-18","Ministry of Defence: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons his Department has initiated an invitation to tender for an Efficiency Assurance Review for additional external and independent assurance of his Department's revised efficiency plan within his Department’s financial forecast.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825421","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-26","<p>The Ministry of Defence calculates that by July 2017 the Single Source Contract Regulations had achieved reductions in contract prices of £313 million.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-26T12:10:43.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825421/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825421/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-18","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will estimate the value of efficiencies created by the operation of the Single Source Contract Regulations 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825422","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-25","<p>NHS England’s statistics publication plan can be accessed online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/12-months-statistics-calendar/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/12-months-statistics-calendar/</a></p><p> </p><p>It confirms that cancelled elective operations data for Quarter 3 2017-18 (which includes December 2017 data) will be published on 8 February 2018.</p><p> </p><p>All published quarterly performance data on cancelled elective operations, which includes national, regional and provider level activity, is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cancelled-elective-operations/cancelled-ops-data/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-25T13:44:07.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825422/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825422/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","Hospitals: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to Question 121387, on hospitals: West Yorkshire, if he will provide that data from 1 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825423","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Government’s Housing White Paper set out a wide ranging approach to driving up build out of planning permissions. <br> <br> In addition, at Autumn Budget 2017, the Government announced that an independent review of build out will be conducted. This will be chaired by the Rt Hon Sir Oliver Letwin MP, with the support of a cross-party panel of experts. The review will consider the significant gap between housing completions, and the amount of planning permissions and land allocated for housing. The review panel will make recommendations for closing this gap, and will report on its findings in 2018.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T17:16:21.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825423/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825423/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-18","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to grant powers to councils to be able to use unused planning permissions.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","123564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825424","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-23","<p>Local authorities are free to borrow and invest in infrastructure for the benefit of local people without prior government consent, subject to assuring themselves that their borrowing costs are affordable.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities can secure contributions from developers to fund infrastructure through the Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL) and section 106 planning obligations. CIL is a flat rate charge on new development that local authorities can use to address the cumulative impact of development in their area. Section 106 planning obligations are negotiated agreements between local planning authorities and developers, and can be used to build infrastructure that will make a development acceptable in planning terms.</p><p> </p><p>The government recognises the importance of infrastructure that supports housing. This is why the Autumn Budget 2017 announced a further £2.7bn for the Housing Infrastructure Fund, which supports infrastructure that unlocks housing, taking total investment in the fund to £5bn.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-01-23T15:24:27.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825424/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825424/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-18","Local Government: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will grant councils the freedom to invest in local infrastructure in new housing developments.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","123565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825425","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Department has not made any assessment of the effectiveness of the General Pharmaceutical Council (GPhC) as a regulator of pharmacy professionals and pharmacy premises. The Professional Standards Authority, which in its review of the GPhC’s performance in 2016-2017, found that the GPhC had met all of the standards for good regulation, including all of the standards for fitness to practise.</p><p> </p><p>Standards to safeguard the health, safety and wellbeing of patients and the public are set by the GPhC. It is important to note that there are very different legal frameworks for upholding these standards and how the regulator deals with these for pharmacy premises as compared to pharmacy professionals. 87% of the pharmacies inspected by the GPhC in 2016-17 were meeting all of the standards it sets. Any pharmacy not achieving all of the standards is required by the GPhC to implement an action plan to improve the services they provide. In this period the GPhC agreed 469 action plans with pharmacies to ensure they improved the services they provide, and 99% of them made the necessary improvements so that they were meeting all of the standards. In the same period 140 cases were made affecting an individual pharmacy professional’s registration.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","123567","2018-01-23T17:21:47.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825425/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825425/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the General Pharmaceutical Council's enforcement of standards for registered pharmacy premises; whether he has made an assessment of the effect of failure to apply such standards to pharmacy owners rather than only pharmacy professionals on the safety of patients; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Sir Kevin Barron","Rother Valley","Sir Kevin Barron","123566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825426","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Department has not made any assessment of the effectiveness of the General Pharmaceutical Council (GPhC) as a regulator of pharmacy professionals and pharmacy premises. The Professional Standards Authority, which in its review of the GPhC’s performance in 2016-2017, found that the GPhC had met all of the standards for good regulation, including all of the standards for fitness to practise.</p><p> </p><p>Standards to safeguard the health, safety and wellbeing of patients and the public are set by the GPhC. It is important to note that there are very different legal frameworks for upholding these standards and how the regulator deals with these for pharmacy premises as compared to pharmacy professionals. 87% of the pharmacies inspected by the GPhC in 2016-17 were meeting all of the standards it sets. Any pharmacy not achieving all of the standards is required by the GPhC to implement an action plan to improve the services they provide. In this period the GPhC agreed 469 action plans with pharmacies to ensure they improved the services they provide, and 99% of them made the necessary improvements so that they were meeting all of the standards. In the same period 140 cases were made affecting an individual pharmacy professional’s registration.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","123566","2018-01-23T17:21:47.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825426/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825426/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of whether the failure to apply sanctions for standards for pharmacy premises has resulted in a disproportionate number of individual pharmacist registrants who have been held to account for professional standards which may have been impacted by the working environment created by pharmacy owners; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Sir Kevin Barron","Rother Valley","Sir Kevin Barron","123567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825427","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>Officials have met with IMPACT-se staff to discuss their report on the Palestinian Authority (PA) 2017 curriculum. The report made some concerning allegations which we are currently assessing. The UK government is working with the Palestinian Ministry of Education and Higher Education to support a high quality education including through its curriculum. Our partnership with the PA includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language and actions that could incite violence or hatred. We continue to urge them to uphold this principle. The UK strongly condemns all forms of violence and deplores incitement.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T17:46:47.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825427/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825427/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Palestinians: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the Memorandum of Understanding between the Palestinian Authority and her Department, signed in 2014, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for its policies of the findings and recommendations of the IMPACT-se report on the Palestinian Authority 2017 curriculum, published in October 2017.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","123568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825428","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-26","<p>I refer the Honourable Member for Mitcham and Morden to my answer to her earlier PQ on this matter (121319) on 15 January. We will continue to raise our concerns around the discrimination of religious minorities in Egypt. This includes concerns over the rights to freedom of expression, association and assembly in Egypt. These rights are essential to improving the protection of Freedom of Religious Belief in Egypt.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-26T13:06:34.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825428/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825428/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-18","Egypt: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his counterpart in the Egyptian Government on the arrest of 25 Ahmadi Muslims in Egypt on the grounds of their religion; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","123569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825429","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Government has ensured superfast broadband (speeds of 24 Mbps or more) is available to over 95% of UK premises and is continuing to invest to extend superfast coverage as far beyond 95% as possible. The Government is also introducing a Universal Service Obligation so that by 2020 everyone across the UK will have a clear, enforceable right to request high speed broadband (speeds of 10 Mbps or more). In the period before 2020, the Government has made a commitment to provide every home and business in the UK with access to basic broadband service (speeds of 2Mbps), which should be sufficient for online banking. A subsided broadband installation is available if the home or business cannot access an affordable broadband service with a speed of at least 2 Mbps.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-08T16:15:17.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825429/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825429/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Bank Services: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to facilitate access to online banking for people without internet access.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","123570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825430","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>The department does not hold or collate this information.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T17:30:36.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825430/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825430/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Disasters Emergency Committee: Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the proportion of donations received by the Disasters Emergency Committee that are from people over the age of 65.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","123571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825431","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Government has provided over £5.9m for the delivery of superfast broadband in Cornwall. According to Thinkbroadband, currently over 90% of premises in Cornwall have access to Superfast Broadband, up from 33% in 2011. The local Superfast Cornwall project has a current delivery contract with BT which will extend coverage to at least a further 3% of premises within Cornwall.</p><p> </p><p>As confirmed in our announcement in December 2017 we are pushing ahead with our plans for a Universal Service Obligation (USO) so that by 2020 everyone across the UK will have a clear, enforceable right to request high speed broadband.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-25T14:47:30.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825431/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825431/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-18","Broadband: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he has taken to facilitate access to superfast broadband for people who live in (a) Cornwall and (b) North Cornwall constituency; and whether he has held discussions with superfast broadband providers on delivering that service.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","123572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825432","Home Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Visa applications are considered to be complex when an Entry Clearance Officer determines that additional information is required in order for a decision to be made. <br>There are no set standards for processing non-straightforward (identified as complex) by the caseworker. However, if an application is complex and expected to take longer than the standard processing timescale, UKVI will write to the customer within the standard processing time and explain what will happen next</p><p>The published information on processing times for visa applications is published as part of the Migration Transparency data, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-23T15:40:14.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825432/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825432/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-18","Visas: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which criteria are applied by UK Visas and Immigration staff when judging a visa application to be non-straightforward; and what service standards govern the (a) processing of such applications and (b) updating the applicant on the status and progress of their application.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","123573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825433","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>My Department continues to develop the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, which aims to improve productivity and reduce economic inequalities across the country. As announced in the Industrial Strategy, we will consult widely on the design of the new Fund later in the year.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-23T13:37:57.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825433/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825433/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-18","EU Grants and Loans: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent progress has been made on the creation of the Shared Prosperity Fund for Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","123574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825434","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-25","<p>At present the vast majority of Electric Vehicle (EV) drivers choose to charge their cars at home, overnight, but adequate availability of public charging is also very important. Thanks to Government policy, a growing private sector and the work of Local Authorities, the UK now has over 11,500 publicly accessible charge points. These include over 900 rapid charge points, giving the UK one of the largest rapid networks in Europe.</p><p>On 17 January, the Committee on Climate Change (CCC) published its report &quot;Plugging the gap: An assessment of future demand for Britain’s electric vehicle public charging network&quot;, which sets out the findings of a new analysis of the optimal Electric Vehicle (EV) public charging infrastructure needed to meet future growth of EVs in Great Britain to 2030. The Government is considering this analysis and expects to publish an updated strategy by end of March this year on the transition to zero emission vehicles.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-25T12:21:39.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825434/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825434/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-18","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of provision of charging points and other infrastructure associated with electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","123575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825435","Department for Education","false","2018-01-23","<p>Local authorities are responsible for funding maintained nursery schools in their area. We are providing supplementary funding of approximately £60 million a year to enable local authorities to protect maintained nursery school funding until 2019-20. Budgets after 2019-20 will be set at the next Spending Review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-23T13:25:07.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825435/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825435/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to provide updated funding formulas for maintained nursery schools.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","123576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825436","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-26","<p>The BEIS Energy Entrepreneurs Fund recently ran a funding call to which such technologies could apply if they could demonstrate that they boosted the UK’s energy security, lowered carbon emissions, or improved energy efficiency. Other Government programmes for which such technologies could be eligible include those operated by Innovate UK including the Energy Catalyst and the “Open” Innovation call. Innovate UK typically run two calls a year under these programmes.</p><p> </p><p>An example of a company currently supported by Government who recycles end of life plastics into heavy fuel oil and other high value products is Recycling Technologies, based in Swindon.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-26T13:25:10.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825436/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825436/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-18","Plastics: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what funding is available for research and development on energy extraction from recycling plastic.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","123577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825437","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The investigation into the disturbance at HMP Birmingham was concluded in early 2017. We have considered its findings and have taken any necessary actions arising from them. We do not intend to publish the report.</p><p> </p><p>We have robust processes in place to closely monitor and manage privately managed prison providers, ensuring that they are providing a safe and secure environment and delivering value for money to the taxpayer. We will not hesitate to take action if and when standards fall short.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T16:01:48.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825437/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825437/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-18","Birmingham Prison: Civil Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the report of Sarah Payne into the riot at HMP Birmingham in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825438","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>My department is in close contact with the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, in Somalia and at headquarter level, on both of these issues. The UK played a leading role in the response to the 2017 drought, making UK Aid available early on and mobilising early contributions from other partners, and we are working closely to ensure that the effective response continues into 2018.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-23T17:42:41.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825438/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825438/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Somalia: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions her Department has had with the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs on a UK aid response to (a) the severe drought and (b) the continuing conflicts in Somalia.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825439","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>The UK hosted an international Conference on Somalia in London in May 2017 at which agreements were reached to work to improve security, strengthen Somalia’s political foundations, and help the economy recover in order to put Somalia on the path to peace and prosperity and break the cycle of persistent humanitarian crises. Our efforts in Somalia – including through the UK aid programme – are designed to support progress in all these areas. The UK played a leading role in responding to the 2017 drought and related food security crisis, and will ensure these efforts continue into 2018.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-23T17:43:38.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825439/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825439/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Somalia: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking, alongside her international counterparts, to secure a long-term solution on (a) food security and (b) general stability in Somalia.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825440","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>A Foreign and Commonwealth Office official attended a conference hosted by Al-Azhar in Cairo on 17 January 2018, which was focused on the issue of Jerusalem.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T14:23:02.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825440/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825440/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-18","Jerusalem","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK Government representatives attended the Egyptian Government's Al-Azhar's international conference in Cairo on the issue of Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","123581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825441","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Information on public sector suppliers within a specific constituency is not held centrally.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-23T15:26:46.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825441/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825441/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Carillion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contracts the UK Government holds with Carillion in (a) Motherwell and Wishaw constituency and (b) Scotland; and what the value of those contracts is.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825442","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-05","<p>If small subcontractors are providing public sector services then we are taking steps to ensure the continuity of those services.</p><p> </p><p>If subcontractors are supporting private sector contracts then their future role depends on their customers.</p><p> </p><p>The action we have taken is designed to keep vital public services running, rather bailing out a commercial company.</p><p> </p><p>We are mindful of the concerns of Carillion employees in the private sector and resources are open to these workers and businesses affected by Carillion’s liquidation who are seeking further information, including:</p><ul><li>a<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/carillion-declares-insolvency-information-for-employees-creditors-and-suppliers" target="_blank"> webpage</a> set up by the Insolvency Service for those affected and seeking advice;</li><li>a<a href="https://www.pwc.co.uk/carillion" target="_blank"> dedicated website</a> set up by the Special Managers, PWC, as well as a dedicated helpline;</li><li>a hotline set up for any employee worried about their pension situation;</li><li>more general advice on business support is available through the BEIS Business Support Hotline; and</li><li>Jobcentre Plus, through its Rapid Response Service, also stands ready to support any employee affected by this announcement.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Alongside this a network of 38 Local Growth Hubs, run in conjunction with the Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP), is also on hand to help businesses of all sizes and in all sectors to access support.</p><p> </p><p>This is a private sector company and taxpayers can’t be expected to bail out a private sector company.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-02-05T14:50:24.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825442/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825442/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department made an assessment of the effect of Carillion's liquidation on the viability of the small businesses in its supply chain in (a) Scotland and (b) the rest of the UK before deciding not to support that company through the bail-out negotiations.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825443","Scotland Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Scotland Office has no contracts with Carillion or its subsidiaries. Ministers and officials of the Scotland Office have had no meetings with representatives of (i) Carillion and (ii) Carillion subsidiaries in those capacities since January 2017.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-01-25T12:55:38.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825443/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825443/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-01-18","Scotland Office: Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have had with representatives of (i) Carillion and (ii) Carillion subsidiaries since January 2017; who attended those meetings; and what was discussed at each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825444","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Secretary of State and I have regular discussions with ministers in other government departments on a range of matters.</p><p> </p><p>We want children to be healthy and well-nourished and the dairy industry makes an important contribution to this. Alongside the European Union (EU) scheme, the Government is already doing a great deal nationally to promote children’s dairy consumption through, for example, the much larger national free Nursery Milk Scheme, and by ensuring the availability of milk for pupils under the School Food Standards, including free milk for disadvantaged pupils. The longer-term approach to the EU Scheme is still under consideration.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","123586","2018-01-23T18:22:20.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825444/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825444/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","School Milk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the number of school children who will be affected by the discontinuance of subsidies from the European School Milk Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","123585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825445","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Secretary of State and I have regular discussions with ministers in other government departments on a range of matters.</p><p> </p><p>We want children to be healthy and well-nourished and the dairy industry makes an important contribution to this. Alongside the European Union (EU) scheme, the Government is already doing a great deal nationally to promote children’s dairy consumption through, for example, the much larger national free Nursery Milk Scheme, and by ensuring the availability of milk for pupils under the School Food Standards, including free milk for disadvantaged pupils. The longer-term approach to the EU Scheme is still under consideration.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","123585","2018-01-23T18:22:20.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825445/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825445/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","School Milk: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on creating a replacement for the European School Milk Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","123586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825446","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>The latest available information on Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) mandatory reconsideration and appeal outcomes can be found in tables 3, 14 and 17 of the ESA Outcomes of Work Capability Assessments quarterly statistics published at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-23T11:40:16.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825446/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825446/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of employment support allowance claim decisions made by the Department for Work and Pensions were overturned at (a) the mandatory reconsideration stage and (b) the tribunal stage in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825447","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>In July 2017, every local area was asked to develop plans to meet winter pressures. This included working with all local partners to consider issues such as demand and capacity, effective discharge and planning for peaks in demand. This local planning may have included consideration on the use and capacity of hospices depending on local circumstances.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-23T14:36:13.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825447/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825447/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","Health Services: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has had discussions with (a) hospice directors and (b) commissioning bodies on the use and capacity of hospices as part of the NHS Winter Resilience Plan.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","123588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825448","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>In 2015/16, the number of staff physically attacked or assaulted at:</p><p>- University Hospital Coventry was 194 involving medical factors<sup>1</sup> and 59 not involving medical factors; and</p><p>- In other healthcare provider settings in Coventry<sup>2</sup>, the number was 3,355 involving medical factors and 277 not involving medical factors.</p><p> </p><p>Employers from across the National Health Service will collect data on physical assaults, and working alongside local police are responsible for protecting their staff. The Department is working with NHS England and NHS Improvement on new arrangements to support NHS and primary care employers to “…take vigorous and immediate action against those who abuse or attack the people who work for and make our NHS”.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p><sup>1</sup>Assaults involving medical factors are the number of physical assaults where the perpetrator did not know what they were doing, or did not know what they were doing was wrong due to medical illness, mental ill health, severe learning disability or treatment administered.</p><p> </p><p><sup>2</sup>The data, extracted from NHS Protect’s “Reported Physical Assaults data for 2015/16 for healthcare settings in Coventry includes University Hospitals Coventry and Warwickshire NHS Trust, Coventry and Warwickshire Partnership NHS Trust and West Midlands Ambulance Trust. Some of the trusts geographical areas cover more than just Coventry.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-23T14:31:17.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825448/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825448/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","NHS: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many healthcare staff have been physically attacked or assaulted at (a) University Hospital Coventry and (b) other healthcare provider settings in Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825449","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>The terms and conditions of the loan are set out in The Loans for Mortgage Interest Regulations 2017 (<a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2017/725/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2017/725/made</a>). A loan agreement has been sent (or will be sent) to all existing customers who wish to take up the offer of a Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI) loan.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-23T11:31:02.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825449/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825449/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to publish the updated terms and conditions of the replacement SMI loan scheme.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","123590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825450","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Information on public sector suppliers within a specific constituency is not held centrally.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","123593","2018-01-23T15:25:56.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825450/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825450/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Carillion: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contracts the Government holds with Carillion in (a) Coventry and (b) Coventry South constituency; and what the value is of those contracts.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825451","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to financial services for all consumers and small businesses in the UK.</p><p>99% of UK personal bank accounts and 95% of small business accounts can be accessed to withdraw cash and deposit cash and cheques over the counter in any of the UK’s network of over 11,600 post offices. It is the operational responsibility of the Post Office to meet its contractual obligations under the agreement it has with the banks to provide banking services.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-23T16:44:23.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825451/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825451/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-18","Post Offices: Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment the Government has made of whether the post office network will have the capacity to meet any increase in demand for banking services after the closure of a number of RBS and NatWest bank branches; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825452","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Information on public sector suppliers within a specific constituency is not held centrally.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","123591","2018-01-23T15:25:56.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825452/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825452/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Carillion: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many contracts the Government awarded to Carillion in Coventry South constituency between (a) 5 May 2010 and 7 May 2015, (b) 8 May 2015 and 13 July 2016, (c) 14 July 2016 and 8 June 2017, (d) 9 June 2017 and 10 July 2017, (e) 11 July 2017 and 29 September 2017 and (f) since 30 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825453","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>This information is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Department has previously published average costs of PIP and ESA mandatory reconsiderations and appeals, which covers direct staff costs only (see Table 24 of Work and Pensions Select Committee PIP and ESA assessments inquiry: supporting statistics ).</p><p> </p><p>The total that DWP has spent on mandatory reconsiderations and appeals includes high level support costs such as management and corporate overheads. These costs cannot be split out from overall Departmental spending on benefit payments, and therefore total Departmental spend on mandatory reconsideration and appeal is not available.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-23T11:40:33.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825453/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825453/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse was of defending decisions made by his Department on employment and support allowance claims taken to tribunal; and what the net gain or loss was in challenging those decisions.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825454","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-23","<p>Carillion is part of a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) consortium currently contracted by Sandwell and West Birmingham Hospitals NHS Trust to undertake the £342 million building project for the new acute hospital on the Queen Elizabeth site in Birmingham and community facilities. NHS Improvement and the Department are working closely with Sandwell and West Birmingham Hospitals NHS Trust and their private sector partners to minimise the impact of the Carillion liquidation and any resulting delay to completion.</p><p> </p><p>There are processes in place in the event of the administration or liquidation of a contractor part way through a build and the PFI companies and their lenders are now in active engagement. There is planning in place to ensure the delay is as minimal as possible.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the NHS Trust, Carillion provide maintenance services to three NHS LIFT Companies in the region (LIFT Birmingham and Solihull; LIFT Sandwell; and LIFT Dudley) which provide a total of 20 primary care centres and facilities. The NHS LIFT Companies have their own contingency plans in place to source these maintenance services from other companies.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-23T14:40:36.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825454/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825454/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-18","Carillion: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the value is of NHS contracts with Carillion in (a) West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825455","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-14","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the Statement made to the House on Monday, 15 January 2018 by the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster (Official Record, vol 634, col 624).</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-14T14:13:32.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825455/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825455/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-18","Carillion: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure that major public sector construction projects in the West Midlands held by Carillion will proceed as planned.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825456","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-25","<p>As part of the first Independent Review of the Work Capability Assessment, Professor Malcolm Harrington recommended a copy of the personalised summary of the assessment report was sent to every claimant.</p><p> </p><p>Following a trial in 2011 evidence suggested a better approach would be to send claimants the Decision Makers justification. This approach was agreed with Professor Harrington and implementation commenced in December 2011. The implementation considered policy, operational and claimant’s requirements. As a result it was agreed that the Decision Maker’s justification will be shared in all adverse decisions, and only shared on request where entitlement has been awarded.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-25T16:34:05.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825456/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825456/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons work capability assessment reports are not released to claimants until a decision has been made on their claim; and if she will review this policy.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","123597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825457","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>Our Ambassador and EU counterparts have called for the release of all prisoners detained for religious beliefs or, as a minimum, that they are brought before a court for public hearing and fair trial, allowing them to defend themselves against any charge. We will continue to raise our concerns on this and other human rights issues with the Government of Eritrea.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-25T17:39:02.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825457/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825457/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-18","Eritrea: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Government of Eritrea on its treatment of religious minorities.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825458","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-25","<p>Scotland stands to benefit substantially from HS2. When Phase One opens in 2026, services will run directly between London and Glasgow, bringing the journey time below 4 hours. When the full HS2 network opens in 2033, journeys between London and Glasgow and Edinburgh will be 3 hr 40 min. The Department for Transport estimates HS2 will deliver around £5bn of benefits to the Scottish economy.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-25T15:14:59.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825458/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825458/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that Scotland benefits fully from the High Speed Two project.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","123599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825459","Home Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Home Office does not centrally hold the information requested.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick  Hurd","123669","2018-01-24T16:19:22.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825459/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825459/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-18","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people were released on uncharged bail in the (a) year prior to and (b) period since the implementation of the Policing and Crime Act 2017; and for each such period what was the average length of time for which a person was bailed.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","123600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825460","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>We published our Equality, Diversity and Inclusion (EDI) strategy for the Defra group in January 2017 which sets out our commitments to EDI from 2017 to 2020. This strategy includes our objectives, how we will achieve these and our success measures in accordance with our requirements under the Public Sector Equality Duty.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-24T15:07:06.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825460/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825460/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when his Department plans to publish its equality objectives for 2017 to 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825461","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-26","<p>The former Lord Chancellor previously announced the beginning of a Post-Implementation Review of the legal aid changes made by the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 (LASPO).</p><p>As the former Lord Chancellor stated we are keen to hear from a range of interested parties and experts as part of the review process. I am currently considering the most effective approach.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-26T12:19:55.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825461/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825461/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-18","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64306, on Legal costs, whether the review of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 will include a public consultation.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","123602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825462","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>On the Secretary of state’s recent visit to Bangladesh in November 2017, she discussed the issue of NGO access to provide support to displaced Rohingya in Bangladesh with the UN and partners in Dhaka. The issue was raised with the government of Bangladesh by FCO Ministers on their joint visit last September, and is raised regularly with the government by officials from the British High Commission in Bangladesh.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T17:33:45.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825462/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825462/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent representations she has made to the Bangladesh Government to give UK humanitarian agencies access to Bangladesh to support displaced Rohingya people.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","123603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825463","Department for Education","false","2018-01-26","<p>Ministers from the Department for Education (DfE) have written to all local authorities and Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) whose areas have been inspected under the Ofsted/Care Quality Commission (CQC) Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) inspection framework; and have written again, after 12 months, to those areas identified by the inspections as having significant weaknesses. These letters follow up the key points raised in the inspection reports, a summary of which is reflected in the one year on report.</p><p> </p><p>The government has provided, since April 2014, over £300 million to support local authorities, working with their partners, including health and schools, to implement the SEND reforms; and we are in the process of procuring further support for 2018-2020.</p><p> </p><p>We have funded training and a SEND leadership programme to support local authorities and health services to deliver their SEND services, which included training on joint commissioning. To improve the knowledge and skills of school staff on good SEND practice we have funded a school improvement programme. This includes a ‘what works’ resource, drawing on evidence-based practice on SEND in good and outstanding schools and colleges.</p><p> </p><p>Where local area performance, such as the commissioning of services, is a particular concern, officials from the DfE working closely with partners, including Department of Health and Social Care and NHS England, have engaged with local areas to provide support and challenge, and have seen a proactive and positive response.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","123606 ; 123617","2018-01-26T12:44:12.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825463/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825463/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions he has had with (a) the Department for Health, (b) school leaders, (c) teaching unions and (d) other professional bodies on the conclusion of the Ofsted Care Quality Commission report, C Report, Local area SEND inspections: one year on, regarding the adequacy of the knowledge and skills of school staff to identify accurately children and young people that need further assessments.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","123604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825464","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government has been engaging and will continue to engage with industry to ensure that this access is maintained.</p><p>LINK, the main scheme behind the UK’s ATM network, has assured us that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK intends to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in areas of deprivation, where demand would not otherwise make one viable, and has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM.</p><p>The Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at <a href="https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network" target="_blank">https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network</a>.</p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p>99% of UK personal bank accounts and 95% of small business accounts can be accessed to withdraw cash and deposit cash and cheques over the counter in any of the UK’s network of over 11,600 post offices.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-23T16:44:55.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825464/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825464/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-18","Post Offices: Cash Dispensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will bring forward legislative proposals to ensure that post offices provide free access to ATMs when there is no other ATM within 1km of that post office.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825465","Department for Education","false","2018-01-26","<p>Ministers from the Department for Education (DfE) have written to all local authorities and Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) whose areas have been inspected under the Ofsted/Care Quality Commission (CQC) Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) inspection framework; and have written again, after 12 months, to those areas identified by the inspections as having significant weaknesses. These letters follow up the key points raised in the inspection reports, a summary of which is reflected in the one year on report.</p><p> </p><p>The government has provided, since April 2014, over £300 million to support local authorities, working with their partners, including health and schools, to implement the SEND reforms; and we are in the process of procuring further support for 2018-2020.</p><p> </p><p>We have funded training and a SEND leadership programme to support local authorities and health services to deliver their SEND services, which included training on joint commissioning. To improve the knowledge and skills of school staff on good SEND practice we have funded a school improvement programme. This includes a ‘what works’ resource, drawing on evidence-based practice on SEND in good and outstanding schools and colleges.</p><p> </p><p>Where local area performance, such as the commissioning of services, is a particular concern, officials from the DfE working closely with partners, including Department of Health and Social Care and NHS England, have engaged with local areas to provide support and challenge, and have seen a proactive and positive response.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","123604 ; 123617","2018-01-26T12:44:12.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825465/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825465/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-18","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans he has to implement the recommendations of the Ofsted Care Quality Commission report, Local area SEND inspections: one year on, published in October 2017, on commissioning of health services for young people up to the age of 25.","true","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","123606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825466","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>Defra did not consult with any external women’s or faith-based organisations on the content of our Equality, Diversity &amp; Inclusion strategy. However we did consult with our employee diversity networks across the Defra group (including our women’s networks), diversity champions and shared this strategy with trade union colleagues.</p><p> </p><p>We are also members of external organisations such as the Employers Network for Equality and Inclusion (ENEI) and seek their advice and links to best practice when considering specific actions to achieve our strategic objectives on EDI.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-24T16:19:52.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825466/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825466/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which women's or faith-based organisations which are not staff networks his Department has consulted as part of the process to update its equality objectives for 2017 to 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825467","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-25","<p>Langside Jobcentre, as of 13 December 2017, had 500 claimants.</p><p> </p><p>Although no specific assessment has been made of the increased footfall at Newlands and Laurieston jobcentres, we know that these sites have the capacity to accommodate the movement of claimants from Langside.</p><p> </p><p>This means we will be able to match the increase in footfall by moving our work coaches, who were previously working in Langside, with their claimants to Newlands and Laurieston jobcentres.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-25T11:48:36.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825467/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825467/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-18","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the increased footfall at (a) Newlands and (b) Laurieston jobcentres resulting from the closure of Langside jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","123608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825468","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-24","<p>The UK regularly engages with UK NGOs in Bangladesh. All NGOs seeking to access to refugee camps and provide support in Bangladesh require the government of Bangladesh's permission to do so. The list of those requesting access is held by the government of Bangladesh.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T17:20:20.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825468/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825468/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-18","Bangladesh: Migrant Camps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate the Government has made on the number of UK humanitarian agencies seeking access to refugee camps in Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","123609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825469","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>Figures on the number of local authority owned dwellings with Category 1 Hazards are available in section F of the local authority housing statistics data return. <br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2016-to-2017</a></p><p><br> Figures are not available at constituency level.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T13:03:28.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825469/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825469/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-18","Housing: Bethnal Green and Bow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of homes with Category 1 Hazards owned by the local authority in Bethnal Green and Bow constituency.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","123610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825471","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>There are eight people working in the Department’s Equality, Diversity and Inclusion (EDI) team, providing EDI support to the Defra group. The department collects diversity data of employees via voluntary self-declaration and this is recorded on our online HR system.</p><p> </p><p>We cannot provide the information as requested for the Equality, Diversity and Inclusion team as, under the Data Protection Act, the small size of the team would risk the anonymity of our employees.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-24T15:11:14.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825471/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/825471/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-18","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people are employed in his Department's Equality, Diversity and Inclusion Team; and what information his Department holds on how many of those staff are (a) male, (b) female, (c) LGBT, (d) disabled, (e) Christian, (f) Muslim, (g) Jewish, (h) Hindu or (i) other belief or lack of belief.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123611"
